2\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u043e \u0441\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0443\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435, \u0414\u043e\u0441\u044c\u0435)]. Kommersant. 10 May 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.unian.ua/world/326282-edina-rosiya-rozrahovue-na-yanukovicha.html The United Russia relies on Yanukovych (\u0404\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0456\u044f \u0440\u043e\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0443\u0454 \u043d\u0430 \u042f\u043d\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u0430)]. [[UNIAN]]. 17 February 2010</ref>\n| european = \n| colours = {{Color box|{{Party of Regions/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Blue]] and {{Color box|white}} [[White]]<ref>Yulia Abibok. ''[https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/odr/party-of-regions-ua-en/ How Ukraine\u2019s old guard are trying to get back into parliament]''. [[openDemocracy]]. 18 July 2019</ref><ref>Georgiy Avdeev. ''[http://patriot-donetsk.ru/6039-regionaly-bez-regionov-chto-zabyli-kupit-belo-golubye.html \"Regionalists\" without regions: What did \"white-blues\" forget to buy? (\u00ab\u0420\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044b\u00bb \u0431\u0435\u0437 \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432\u00bb: \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0431\u044b\u043b\u0438 \u043a\u0443\u043f\u0438\u0442\u044c \u00ab\u0431\u0435\u043b\u043e-\u0433\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0431\u044b\u0435\u00bb?)]. Patriotic Forces of Donbass. 1 June</ref><ref>Oksana Denisova. ''[https://www.pravda.com.ua/rus/articles/2007/09/19/4424294/ How Oranges and White-Blues through middle of a night were dividing the Maidan (\u041a\u0430\u043a \u043e\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0436\u0435\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0438 \u0431\u0435\u043b\u043e-\u0433\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0431\u044b\u0435 \u041c\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0438 \u043d\u043e\u0447\u0438 \u0434\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043b\u0438)]''. [[Ukrayinska Pravda]]. 19 September 2007</ref><ref>Liubov Borschevskaya. ''[https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/810329 Party of Regions creates work places]''. Kommersant.ru. 2 October 2007</ref>\n| website = {{url|http://partyofregions.ua/}}\n| country = Ukraine\n}}\n[[File:Makeevka 086.jpg|thumb|The office of Party of Regions in [[Makiivka]], 2009]]\nThe '''Party of Regions''' ({{lang-uk|\u041f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0456\u044f \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0456\u0432|Partija rehioniv}}, {{IPA-uk|\u02c8p\u0251rt\u207d\u02b2\u207eij\u0250 re\u0266i\u02c8\u0254n\u207d\u02b2\u207eiu\u032f|pron}}; {{lang-ru|\u041f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432|Partija regionov}}) is a [[Russophilia|pro-Russia]]<ref>[http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2012/12/15/6979798/ Regionalists principally will speak in Russian - Bondarenko. (\"\u0420\u0435\u0433\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0438\" \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432\u043e \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0442\u044c \u0432\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0430\u0442\u0438 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u044e - \u0411\u043e\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e)]. [[Ukrayinska Pravda]]. 2012-12-14</ref><ref>[[Taras Kuzio|Kuzio, T]]. ''[http://commonweb.unifr.ch/artsdean/pub/gestens/f/as/files/4760/25737_184750.pdf Populism in Ukraine]''. [[Problems of Post-Communism]]. Vol.57. \"[[M. E. Sharpe]]\". 2010. p.15</ref> [[political party]] of [[Ukraine]] created in late 1997 that then grew to be the biggest party of Ukraine between 2006 and 2014. Since the February [[2014 Ukrainian revolution]], the party has not competed in elections and most of its representatives have left the party to continue their careers in other parties.<ref name=\"en.ria.ru\"/><ref name=Rs15BBCU/> The best known former party members are former [[Prime Minister of Ukraine|Prime Minister]] [[Mykola Azarov]] and former [[President of Ukraine]] [[Viktor Yanukovych]];<ref name=AzarovLPR23410/> both fled to [[Russia]] in February 2014.<ref name=AzYaPorftR>[http://www.rferl.org/content/ukraine-ex-pm-azarov-forms-salvation-committee/27167032.html Ex-PM Azarov, In Moscow, Proclaims 'Salvation Committee' For Ukraine], [[Radio Free Europe]] (3 August 2015)<br />[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/243934.html Ukraine accuses Russia of breaking CIS agreements over Yanukovych extradition], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (12 January 2015)</ref>\n\nThe party was created on 26 October 1997, just prior to the [[1998 Ukrainian parliamentary election]]s, under the name of '''Party of Regional Revival of Ukraine'''<ref name=DATA/> and led by [[Volodymyr Vasylyovych Rybak|Volodymyr Rybak]]. Throughout its existence the party has contained different political groups with diverging ideological outlooks.<ref name=\"Max Bader Center\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=uD-9tyD2KrMC&pg=PA82 Against All Odds:Aiding Political Parties in Georgia and Ukraine] by [[Max Bader]], [[Vossiuspers UvA]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-9056296315}} (page 82)</ref><ref name=SFFUkW>[http://ukrainianweek.com/Politics/60083 Strange Familiar Faces], [[The Ukrainian Week]] (15 September 2012)</ref><ref name=\"ideologicalsplits\">[http://ukrainianweek.com/Politics/17910 Ideological Splits], [[The Ukrainian Week]] (10 March 2011)</ref>\n\nThe party was reorganized later in 2001 when it united with several others. According to the party's leadership in 2002, from the creation of the party to the end of 2001 the number of members jumped from 30,000 to 500,000.<ref>[http://content.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,226894,00.html Whose Ukraine Is It Anyway?], ''[[TIME Magazine]]/[[Transitions online]]'', April 4, 2002</ref> The party claims to ideologically defend and uphold the [[Minority rights|rights]] of [[Russians in Ukraine|ethnic Russians]] and [[Russian language in Ukraine|speakers of the Russian language]] in [[Ukraine]]. It originally supported president [[Leonid Kuchma]] and joined the pro-government [[For United Ukraine]] alliance during the [[2002 Ukrainian parliamentary election|parliamentary elections]] on 30 March 2002.\n\nIts electoral and financial base has always been located primarily in the east and south-east of Ukraine, where it got wide popular electoral support.<ref name=support>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100514122941/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/66496/ Poll: Political forces of Tigipko, Yatseniuk, Communist Party in Top 5 of April rating of parties], [[Kyiv Post]] (12 May 2010)</ref> In the eastern Ukrainian [[Donetsk Oblast]] the party claimed in 2010 to have over 700,000 members. The party was supported mostly by people older than 45 years.<ref name=support/>\n\nIn 2010, the party candidate [[Viktor Yanukovych]] won the [[2010 Ukrainian presidential election|presidential elections]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/yanukovich-declared-winner-in-ukraine-poll-1899552.html |title=Yanukovich declared winner in Ukraine poll  | location=London |work=The Independent |first1=Pavel |last1=Polityuk |first2=Richard |last2=Balmforth |date=15 February 2010}}<br />{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8535778.stm |title=Viktor Yanukovych sworn in as Ukraine president | work=BBC News |date=25 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nDue to the rule of the party in Crimea particularly in 2010\u20132014, it gave a new meaning for \"Makedonians\" ({{lang-ru|\u043c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0446\u044b}}) as the Makeevka-Donetsk clan associated with the Crimean Prime Ministers [[Vasyl Dzharty]] and [[Anatoliy Mohyliov]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=O6jDBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT415&lpg=PT415&dq=%D0%9F%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%8F+%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B3%D0%B8%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B2+%D0%BC%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%BD%D1%86%D1%8B&source=bl&ots=nExRYaEne7&sig=ACfU3U1o3paIxhRs0tylERPlnrU_eAVxnw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj_5f2gmIboAhVJeKwKHWiUAJgQ6AEwB3oECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=%D0%9F%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%8F%20%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B3%D0%B8%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B2%20%D0%BC%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%BD%D1%86%D1%8B&f=false Russia in global politics. The new game rules with rules (compilations) (\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u0433\u043b\u043e\u0431\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0435. \u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0438\u0433\u0440\u044b \u0431\u0435\u0437 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b (\u0441\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0438\u043a))]</ref><ref>Zakhar Samsonov. ''[https://ru.krymr.com/a/sevastopol-makedonci-na-marshe/29755120.html Sevastopol: \"Makedonians\" are marching (\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c: \u00ab\u043c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0446\u044b\u00bb \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u0440\u0448\u0435)]''. [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]. 7 February 2019</ref><ref>Oleg Glavatskiy, Valeriy Kosarev. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=YKJyDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT198&lpg=PT198&dq=%D0%9F%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%8F+%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B3%D0%B8%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B2+%D0%BC%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%BD%D1%86%D1%8B&source=bl&ots=7c7fi8wbeO&sig=ACfU3U2CQLvv4Rs35NvyerP3wEfYoIwbrw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiyuq_amoboAhVBMawKHahUCpw4ChDoATAAegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=%D0%9F%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%8F%20%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B3%D0%B8%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B2%20%D0%BC%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%BD%D1%86%D1%8B&f=false The Crimean choice (\u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440)]''.</ref><ref>Borislav Kashikhin, Nadezhda Isaeva. ''[https://primechaniya.ru/sevastopol/stati/mezhdu-udmurtami-i-makedoncami-blok-chalogo-pricenivaetsya-k-sablinu Between \"Udmurts\" and \"Makedonians\": The Chaly Bloc is pre-estimating Sablin (\u041c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443 \u00ab\u0443\u0434\u043c\u0443\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043c\u0438\u00bb \u0438 \u00ab\u043c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0430\u043c\u0438\u00bb: \u0431\u043b\u043e\u043a \u0427\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0432\u0430\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u043a \u0421\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0443)]''. Primechaniya.ru. 13 February 2019</ref><ref>Petr Kozlov. ''[https://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/characters/2015/03/16/esli-eto-imelo-opredelennuyu-rezhissuru---rezhisseru-nuzhno-postavit-pyat-s-plyusom \"If it had particular a stage directing, the stage director had to be given a five with mark (\u00ab\u0415\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u044d\u0442\u043e \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043b\u043e \u043e\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0443\u044e \u0440\u0435\u0436\u0438\u0441\u0441\u0443\u0440\u0443, \u0440\u0435\u0436\u0438\u0441\u0441\u0435\u0440\u0443 \u043d\u0443\u0436\u043d\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u044c \u043f\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0441 \u043f\u043b\u044e\u0441\u043e\u043c\u00bb)]''. [[Vedomosti]]. 16 March 2015</ref>\n\nThe party won 185 seats in the [[Ukrainian parliament]] in the [[2012 Ukrainian parliamentary election]].<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/126937.html#.UUzMyKnCus0 Party of Regions gets 185 seats in Ukrainian parliament, Batkivschyna 101 - CEC], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (12 November 2012)</ref> On 12 December 2012 it formed a [[parliamentary faction]] of 210 deputies.<ref name=\"PRmakes185210\">[http://www.unian.info/politics/727272-it-was-announced-about-creation-of-5-factions-in-vru-party-of-regions-batkivshchyna-udar-svoboda-and-cpu.html It was announced about creation of 5 factions in VRU \u2013 Party of Regions, Batkivshchyna, UDAR, Svoboda and CPU], [[Ukrainian Independent Information Agency]] (12 December 2012)</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2014 Ukrainian revolution]] on February 20, 2014, several party members called for the disintegration of Ukraine and a union with the [[Russian Federation]]. [[Oleksandr Yefremov]], leader of the Ukrainian parliamentary faction in full support of these proposed actions,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140301040756/http://lb.ua/news/2014/02/20/256314_efremov_edet_lugansk_obsuzhdat.html Yefremov travels to Luhansk to discuss possibility of the separation of the South-East - source]. LB. February 20, 2014</ref> and [[Vladimir Konstantinov (politician)|Vladimir Konstantinov]], chairman of the Supreme Council of the [[Autonomous Republic of Crimea]] went to Luhansk to support these decisive actions.<ref>[http://krymtatar.in.ua/krimskij-spiker-u-moskvi-pogrozhuye-priyednannyam-krimu-do-rosiyi/ The Crimean speaker in Moscow threatens of the Crimea's secession to Russia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413130058/http://krymtatar.in.ua/krimskij-spiker-u-moskvi-pogrozhuye-priyednannyam-krimu-do-rosiyi/ |date=2014-04-13 }}. The Crimean Tatar question. February 21, 2014</ref> On 23 February 2014 the Party of Regions condemned and disassociated itself from [[Victor Yanukovych]] for corruption, \"criminal orders\", his escape, and \"cowardice\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://partyofregions.ua/en/news/5309dfd9f620d2f70b000031|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140308073834/http://partyofregions.ua/en/news/5309dfd9f620d2f70b000031|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 March 2014|title=Address of the PARTY OF REGIONS faction to compatriots|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> The following months more than 120 [[Member of Parliament|MP]]s left the party's parliamentary faction.<ref name=\"PRmakes185210\"/><ref name=\"PoRMPGKP8414\">[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/party-of-regions-keeps-losing-members-voters-342580.html Party of Regions keeps losing members, voters], [[Kyiv Post]] (8 April 2014)</ref><ref name=\"20quitPoR3614\"/> Many members of the party became objects of the so called \"trash bucket challenge\".<ref>Tom Balmforth. ''[https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-lustration-trash-can-justice/26616901.html Frustrated Ukrainian Activists Dishing Out 'Trash-Bucket Justice']''. [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]. 2 October 2014</ref><ref>Roland Oliphant. ''[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/11145381/Up-to-a-dozen-Ukraine-officials-dumped-in-wheelie-bins.html Up to a dozen Ukraine officials dumped in wheelie bins]''. [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]. 07 Oct 2014</ref><ref>Ishaan Tharoor. ''[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2014/09/16/watch-ukrainian-politician-gets-dumped-in-the-trash/ Watch: Ukrainian politician gets dump in the trash]''. [[Washington Post]]. 16 September 2014</ref><ref>Katya Gorchinskaya. ''[https://www.kyivpost.com/article/content/reform-watch/frustrated-over-lack-of-justice-ukrainians-throw-officials-to-trash-video-366120.html?cn-reloaded=1 Frustrated over lack of justice, Ukrainians throw officials in trash (VIDEO)]''. [[Kyiv Post]]. 26 September 2014</ref>\n\nThe party did not participate in the [[2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election|2014 parliamentary elections]].<ref name=\"en.ria.ru\">[http://sputniknews.com/politics/20140914/192930339.html Ukraine's Party of Regions Refuses to Participate in Rada Elections], [[RIA Novosti]] (23 September 2014)</ref><ref name=OBBBCU>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/politics/2014/09/140922_opposition_bloc_vc.shtml What distinguishes the \"opposition bloc\" of the Party of Regions?], [[BBC Ukrainian]] (23 September 2014)</ref> In the following months, the majority of its representatives continued their political careers predominantly with [[Opposition Bloc]], [[Revival (Ukraine)|Revival]] or [[Our Land (Ukraine)|Our Land]].<ref name=Rs15BBCU>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/politics/2015/09/150915_nash_kray_local_election_vc \"Revival\" \"our land\": Who picks up the legacy of \"regionals\"], [[BBC Ukrainian]] (16 September 2015)<br />{{in lang|uk}} [http://m.tyzhden.ua/publication/147658 Party of Regions: Snake return], [[The Ukrainian Week]] (2 October 2015)</ref><ref name=\"potoibppd23okt15\">{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2015/10/22/7085788/ Activists noticed that most ex-Regions are on lists of Poroshenko], [[Ukrayinska Pravda]] (22 October 2015)</ref> At same time, due to [[annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation]] and after [[Vladimir Konstantinov]] announced of reorganization of the Party of Regions Crimean branch,<ref>[https://ria.ru/20140312/999173198.html Party of Regions in Crimea will be reorganized, announced the head of the Supreme Council (\u041f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0432 \u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c\u0443 \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0440\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0430, \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u0412\u0421)]. [[RIA Novosti]]. 12 March 2014</ref><ref>[https://www.segodnya.ua/politics/v-krymu-pereimenuyut-partiyu-regionov-konstantinov-502297.html In Crimea Party of Regions will be renamed, Konstantinov (\u0412 \u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c\u0443 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0443\u044e\u0442 \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044e \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u2013 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432)]. [[Segodnya]]. 13 March 2014</ref> members of Party of Regions joined the [[United Russia]].<ref>Andrei Sambros. ''[https://novayagazeta.ru/articles/2015/07/08/64823-kadrovye-chistki-v-krymu-chto-eto-bylo Cleansing of cadres in Crimea: what was it]''. [[Novaya Gazeta]]. 7 July 2015</ref><ref>Petr Bologov. ''[https://republic.ru/posts/l/1157543 How again Party of Regions won election in Crimea (\u041a\u0430\u043a \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u043e\u043f\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0432\u044b\u0438\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u044b \u0432 \u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c\u0443)]''. Republic.ru. 15 September 2014</ref><ref>Pavel Krivosheev. ''[https://ru.krymr.com/a/edinaya-rossiya-partiya-vlasti-no-ne-naroda-krymskie-aktivisty/30317513.html \"United Russia\" is the party of government, but not people\", the Crimea activists (\u00ab\u0415\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f\u00bb \u2013 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438, \u043d\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430\u00bb \u2013 \u043a\u0440\u044b\u043c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b)]''. [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]. 10 December 2019</ref> Officially according to the [[Telegraph Agency of the Soviet Union]] (TASS) and the former leader of the Crimean Party of Region Konstantinov, there is no succession of the United Russia Crimean branch from the Party of Regions Crimean branch,<ref>[https://tass.ru/politika/1102562 In Crimea was created a regional branch of the \"United Russia\" party (\u0412 \u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c\u0443 \u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043e\u0442\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0438 \"\u0415\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f\")]. TASS. 7 April 2014</ref> but, according to several local news resources from Sevastopol, in reality it was organized from former activists of Party of Regions and Russian Unity.<ref>Nataliya Nazaruk. ''[https://sevastopol.su/news/partiyu-vlasti-v-krymu-na-vybory-povedut-aksyonov-i-konstantinov At election the ruling party in Crimea will be led by Aksyonov and Konstantinov (\u041f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044e \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0432 \u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0443\u0442 \u0410\u043a\u0441\u0451\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432)]''. ForPost. 14 June 2019</ref><ref>Stanislav Smagin. ''[https://politconservatism.ru/articles/kak-rossijskie-partii-prishli-v-krym-i-sevastopol How Russian parties came to Crimea and Sevastopol (\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0448\u043b\u0438 \u0432 \u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c \u0438 \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c)]''. Russkaya Ideya. 6 June 2019</ref><ref>[https://nts-tv.com/news/dmitriy-sablin-bolshaya-chast-chlenov-edinoy-rossi-12931/ Dmitriy Sablin: Bigger portion of the United Russia members in Sevastopol are former members of Party of Regions (\u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043d: \u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0447\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u00ab\u0415\u0434\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438\u00bb \u0432 \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0435 \u2013 \u0431\u044b\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0447\u043b\u0435\u043d\u044b \u00ab\u041f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0420\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432\u00bb)]. Sevastopol Independent Television. 9 February 2019</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Party of Regional Revival of Ukraine===\nThe founding congress of the Party of Regional Revival of Ukraine was held on 26 October 1997 in [[Kiev]].<ref name=DEN/> The first leader of the party was the mayor of [[Donetsk]], [[Volodymyr Vasylyovych Rybak|Volodymyr Rybak]].<ref name=DEN/> On 6 November 1997, the Party of Regional Revival of Ukraine was registered at the Ukrainian Ministry of Justice.<ref name=DATA>{{in lang|uk}} [http://da-ta.com.ua/mon_mainnews/840.htm \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0456\u044f \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0456\u0432], Database DATA</ref> On 27 November 1997 there took place the 1st Party Congress, which adopted the electoral party list and platform for the next elections. Already on 13 January 1998 a parliamentary faction was created in the [[parliament of Ukraine]], the Party of Regional Revival of Ukraine (head of coordination council \u2013 [[Gennadiy Samofalov]]).\n\nDuring the [[1998 Ukrainian parliamentary election|1998 parliamentary elections]] the Party of Regional Revival of Ukraine won 0.90% of the votes.<ref name=DATA/> A single party representative was elected to the [[Ukrainian Parliament]] by winning one constituency at the regular elections.<ref name=DEN>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.day.kiev.ua/uk/article/podrobici/ilyuzorna-idiliya \u0406\u043b\u044e\u0437\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0430 \u0456\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0456\u044f], ''[[Den (newspaper)|Den]]'' (7 February 2007)</ref> The party was among the top 10 in [[Chernivtsi Oblast|Chernivtsi]] and [[Donetsk Oblast]]s. [[Volodymyr Vasylyovych Rybak|Volodymyr Rybak]] was the winner of constituency number 45 in Donetsk Oblast.<ref name=CECU21998>{{cite web|url=http://www.cvk.gov.ua/pls/vd2002/webproc0e?kodvib=11&rejim=0 |title=Elections of Peoples Deputies, 1998 |work=Central Election Commission of Ukraine |date=29 November 1998 |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303173047/http://www.cvk.gov.ua/pls/vd2002/webproc0e?kodvib=11&rejim=0 |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2nd Party Congress that took place in two stages during the spring of 1999 it was decided to support the presidential candidate [[Leonid Kuchma]] for the next presidential elections. It was recommended that the candidate include in his election campaign propositions of the Party of Regional Revival of Ukraine, including one on granting the [[Russian language]] official status. In the summer of 1999, the party entered the electoral bloc \"Our choice - Leonid Kuchma\", consisting of 23 parties and led by [[Yevhen Kushnaryov]], who endorsed incumbent [[Ukrainian President|President]] [[Leonid Kuchma]] in the [[1999 Ukrainian presidential election|presidential election of 1999]].<ref name=DEN/>\n\n===Creation of the Party of Regions===\nOn 17 November 2000, the 3rd Extraordinary Party Congress adopted the merger of five political parties, [[For Beautiful Ukraine]] ([[Leonid Chernovetsky]]), [[All-Ukrainian Party of Pensioners]] (A. Kapusta), [[Party of Labor (Ukraine)|Party of Labor]] (Valentyn Landyk), [[Solidarity (Ukraine)|Party of Solidarity of Ukraine]] ([[Petro Poroshenko]]), and Party of Regional Revival of Ukraine ([[Volodymyr Vasylyovych Rybak|Volodymyr Rybak]]), into a new one under the name of Party of Regional Revival \"Labor Solidarity of Ukraine\". The co-leaders of the new political polity became [[Valentyn Landyk]], [[Petro Poroshenko]], and [[Volodymyr Vasylyovych Rybak|Volodymyr Rybak]]. Also, prior to the merger the [[Solidarity (Ukraine)|Party of Solidarity of Ukraine]] was completely abandoned by its base party of [[Serhiy Dovhan]], the [[Peasant Party of Ukraine]], which dissolved its union with Solidarity. On February 21, 2001, the [[Ministry of Justice (Ukraine)|Ministry of Justice]] registered the newly established Party of Regional Revival \"Labour Solidarity of Ukraine\".\n\nOn March 3, 2001, at the 3rd Party Congress, the party changed its name to Party of Regions. At the congress [[Mykola Azarov]], who at that time was chairman of the [[State Tax Administration of Ukraine]], was elected the party leader, but soon resigned in December 2001,<ref name=\"glob\">[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/parties.htm Ukraine Political Parties], GlobalSecurity.org</ref> being replaced by his deputy and at that time Vice Prime Minister [[Volodymyr Semynozhenko]].<ref name=CEU2/> In an interview with the newspaper ''Den'' ({{lang-uk|\u0414\u0435\u043d\u044c}}) on 6 March 2001, Azarov said that he agreed to become the chairman for a brief period \"until the party nominated a leader who will claim the office of the President of Ukraine in 2004\".<ref name=CEU1/> In December 2001 the Party of Regions member Ihor Yushchko was appointed Minister of Finance of Ukraine.<ref name=CEU2/> On 21 March 2001, the [[Ministry of Justice (Ukraine)|Ministry of Justice]] re-registered the party under the number 939 with the older date of registration.\n\nOn 23 May 2001, the party signed an agreement of partnership and cooperation with the party [[Labour Ukraine]] ([[Serhiy Tihipko]]), and on 7 June 2001, with the [[People's Party (Ukraine)|Agrarian Party of Ukraine]].\n\n'''Regions of Ukraine''' was the parliamentary wing of the Party of Regions; it was created at the end of March 2001<ref name=CEU2>[http://pdc.ceu.hu/archive/00001231/01/6.pdf 2001 Political sketches: too early for summing up], [[Central European University]] (January 4, 2002)</ref> after several deputies defected from their original faction. Critics claimed the deputies were \"lured away\" from those other factions by pressure and analysts claimed most of them had nothing to do with the new party.<ref name=CEU1>[http://pdc.ceu.hu/archive/00001265/01/1.pdf New \u00abregion\u00bb formed in Ukrainian Parliament], [[Central European University]] (26 March 2001)</ref> Nine out of seventeen members of the faction had their political and business roots in the [[Donetsk Oblast|Donetsk region]].<ref name=CEU2/> In July 2002 the party had a faction of 24 people (one deputy left the faction later).<ref name=UUPAnie>[http://www.ditext.com/danieri/politics.html Understanding Ukrainian Politics: Power, Politics, and Institutional Design] by [[Paul D'Anieri]], [[M.E. Sharpe]], 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-7656-1811-5}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2001, Solidarity announced it would \"be as a single bloc\".<ref name=CEU1/> (Eventually the (Solidarity) party became part of the [[Viktor Yushchenko Bloc Our Ukraine]] during the 2002 parliamentary elections.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=H23Pv4Ik3vMC&pg=PA391 Communist and Post-Communist Parties in Europe], [[Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht]], 2008, {{ISBN|3-525-36912-3}}  (page 391)</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2002 Ukrainian parliamentary election|Ukrainian parliamentary election]] the party was a member of the [[For United Ukraine]] [[electoral alliance|electoral bloc]].<ref name=DATA/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zaedu.org.ua/index.phtml?razd=party |title=parties of the \"Za Yedynu Ukrayinu\" bloc |accessdate=2008-02-25 |date=2002-11-24 |work=Za Yediny Ukrayinu! |language=Ukrainian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041106203745/http://www.zaedu.org.ua/index.phtml?razd=party |archivedate=2004-11-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was then led by [[Volodymyr Semynozhenko]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zaedu.org.ua/index.phtml?razd=leaders |title=Leaders of the \"Za Yedynu Ukrayinu\" bloc |accessdate=2008-02-25 |date=2002-11-24 |work=Za Yediny Ukrayinu! |language=Ukrainian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041208203028/http://www.zaedu.org.ua/index.phtml?razd=leaders |archivedate=2004-12-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFrom 21 November 2002 until 7 December 2004, [[Viktor Yanukovych]] was [[Prime Minister of Ukraine]].\n\nAt a congress held on 19 April 2003 [[Viktor Yanukovych]] was elected party leader, succeeding [[Volodymyr Semynozhenko]].<ref name=Azarovleader>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110122154153/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/60929/ Yanukovych suspends his membership in Party of Regions, hands over party leadership to Azarov], ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' (3 March 2010)</ref> At that time the party had 20 seats in parliament.<ref>[http://www.ecoi.net/file_upload/1329_1200471485_ukraine-april-2003.pdf UKRAINE COUNTRY ASSESSMENT April 2003], [[ecoi.net]] (April 2003)</ref>\n\n===Electoral breakthrough===\nThe party shifted its political ideology to the [[left-wing politics|left]] and became much more [[populism|populist]] in nature before the [[2004 Ukrainian presidential election]] and, as a result, Yanukovych won over a large part of the [[Communist Party of Ukraine|Communist party's]] electorate in eastern Ukraine. The party announced support for making [[Russian language|Russian]] a second [[official language]] in Ukraine, a pro-Russian foreign policy, and increased social spending. It also advocates the regionalist ideology, and many members support making Ukraine a [[federation]].\n\nThe Party of Regions moved to opposition after its candidate, Viktor Yanukovych, lost the 2004 presidential election. The party leader first claimed an electoral victory, but strong allegations of [[electoral fraud]] triggered a series of events commonly known as the [[Orange Revolution]]. In the re-run of the presidential election ordered by the country's [[Supreme Court of Ukraine|Supreme Court]], Viktor Yanukovych lost the election to [[Viktor Yushchenko]].\n\nThe Party claimed to be a victim of a political persecution campaign organised by the new government, also because [[Borys Kolesnykov]], the head of the regional party branch and of the Donetsk regional council, was arrested in April 2005 and charged with criminal extortion.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110209072810/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/36646/ Lutsenko suggests Regions Party to deal with Piskun, who sanctioned proceedings against Kolesnykov], [[Kyiv Post]] (3 March 2009)</ref> The Party of Regions claimed this was an act of political repression, while the authorities believed that Kolesnykov had links to [[organized crime|organised crime]] and his arrest was a purely criminal matter. The [[Council of Europe]] called the investigation \"in full compliance with European standards\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ebjEVjJ-DcAC&pg=PA580 Countries at the crossroads: a survey of democratic governance] by Sanja Tatic & Christopher Walker, [[Rowman & Littlefield Publishers]], 2006, {{ISBN|0742558010}}/{{ISBN|978-0742558014}} (page 580)</ref> Kolesnykov has since been cleared of charges and released from pre-trial detention.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100125161608/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/57719 Yanukovych\u2019s inner circle], [[Kyiv Post]] (24 January 2010)</ref>\n\nThe party signed a collaboration agreement in 2005 with [[Russia]]'s \"[[United Russia]]\".<ref name=PoRUR>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091124000315/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/53358/ Party of Regions hopes for strengthening collaboration with 'United Russia' party], [[Kyiv Post]] (22 November 2009)</ref>\n\n[[United States|American]] consultant [[Paul J. Manafort]] has advised the party and  Yanukovych since 2005.<ref name=LOmoney>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091123085548/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/53251 Paid advisers descend on candidates, nation], [[Kyiv Post]] (19 November 2009)</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/en/news_print/2006/5/15/5185.htm|title=Spin Doctors at elections 2006: those who worked for Yanukovych, Akhmetov, Tymoshenko, Medvedchuk\u2026|work= [[Ukrayinska Pravda]]|date=10 May 2006}}{{dead link|date=March 2016}}{{cbignore}}</ref> \n[[Image:Ukrainian parliamentary election 2006 (PoR)v.PNG|thumb|right|200px|Map showing the results of POR the percentage of total national vote per region for the 2006 parliamentary election.]]\n\n====2006 Parliamentary Election results====\n{{main|2006 Ukrainian parliamentary election}}\nAt the [[2006 Ukrainian parliamentary election|parliamentary elections]] on 26 March 2006, the party gained 32.14%<ref name=DATA/> of votes and 186 (out of 450) seats in the [[Verkhovna Rada]] (the Ukrainian Parliament), forming the largest parliamentary group. On 6 July 2006, the [[Socialist Party of Ukraine]] abandoned the \"[[Orange Revolution|Orange Coalition]]\" between [[Our Ukraine (political party)|Our Ukraine]] and the [[Yulia Tymoshenko Bloc]] following the failure of each bloc to reach agreement on the formation of a governing coalition.\n\nOn 10 July 2006 a new parliamentary majority titled the \"anti-crisis coalition\", led by the Party of Regions and including the Socialist Party and the [[Communist Party of Ukraine|Communist Party]], was formed, nominating [[Viktor Yanukovych]] to the post of prime minister.\n\nThe coalition remained in office until the [[2007 Ukrainian parliamentary election|special parliamentary elections]] held in September 2007.\n\nAt the [[2006 Crimean parliamentary election]] the party was part of the ''[[For Yanukovych!]]'' [[election bloc]].<ref>{{in lang|ru}} [http://www.rosbalt.ru/ukraina/2009/10/06/677872.html], \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0431\u0430\u043b\u0442.RU (06/10/2009)</ref>\n\nOn 19 January 2007, [[Yevhen Kushnaryov]], a member of the Party of Regions, died in [[Izium]] as a result of an accidental gunshot wound received while hunting.\n\nIn mid-2007, the [[Ukrainian Republican Party]] and [[Labour Ukraine]] merged into the Party of Regions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=11768533&PageNum=0|title=Party merger|work=[[ITAR-TASS]]}}{{dead link|date=March 2016}}{{cbignore}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Ukrainian parliamentary election 2007 (PoR)v.PNG|thumb|right|200px|Map showing the results of the Party of Regions (percentage of total national vote) per region for the 2007 parliamentary election.]]\n\n====2007 Parliamentary Election results====\n{{main|2007 Ukrainian parliamentary election}}\n{{see also|List of the Party of Regions members of the parliament of Ukraine, 2007-2012}}\nAt the [[2007 Ukrainian parliamentary election|parliamentary elections]] held on 30 September 2007, the party won 175 seats (losing 11 seats) out of 450 seats with 34.37% of the total national vote.<ref name=DATA/> The party received the highest number of votes, with a swing of +2.23% in comparison to the 2006 vote.\n\nFollowing the formation of a governing coalition between Our Ukraine and the [[Yulia Tymoshenko Bloc]] and the election of [[Yulia Tymoshenko]] as prime minister on 18 December 2007, the Party of Regions formed the parliamentary opposition.\n\nOn 13 March 2009, Victor Yanukovych stated the Party of Regions was ready to unite into a coalition with its archrivals<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.unian.info/politics/143001-aliens-took-tymoshenko-on-their-flying-saucer.html|title=Aliens took Tymoshenko on their flying saucer?|publisher=[[UNIAN]]|date=5 September 2008|accessdate=5 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.interfax.com.ua/en/news/main-news/174313/|title=Regions Party ready to form coalition 'to save country'|publisher=[[Interfax Ukraine]]|date=8 October 2008|accessdate=8 October 2008}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> the [[Yulia Tymoshenko Bloc]] (BYuT). He noted that: \"We are ready to unite, but only on the base of the program on struggle with crisis\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.unian.info/politics/200037-party-of-regions-is-ready-to-unite-with-byut-yanukovych.html|title=Party of Regions is ready to unite with BYUT\u2013 Yanukovych|publisher=[[UNIAN]]|date=13 March 2008|accessdate=}}</ref> The previous day the deputy leader of the Bloc of Yulia Tymoshenko faction, Andriy Portnov, said that the union of his political force with the Party of Regions was highly improbable, but that the union of the BYuT and the Party of Regions could be possible after the [[2010 Ukrainian presidential election|next Ukrainian presidential elections]].<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/9838.html BYT says union Party of Regions highly improbable], [[Interfax|Interfax-Ukraine]] (13 March 2008)</ref> [[Prime Minister of Ukraine|Prime Minister]] [[Yulia Tymoshenko]] stated on 17 March 2009 that her bloc was ready to join efforts with the Regions Party to pass certain bills in the [[Ukrainian parliament]] (Verkhovna Rada). \"You are a representative of the Regions Party, [and] I represent the BYuT. It's time to join efforts for the benefit of the country,\" Tymoshenko said.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.interfax.com.ua/eng/main/10061|title=BYT ready to join efforts with Regions Party to pass law on aviation development, says Tymoshenko|work=[[Interfax|Interfax-Ukraine]]|date=17 March 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722011518/http://www.interfax.com.ua/eng/main/10061/|archivedate=22 July 2012}}</ref> On 30 March 2009 Victor Yanukovych stated he did not believe in the possibility of forming a coalition with the Yulia Tymoshenko Bloc in the current parliament. At the same time he added that \"it would be necessary to agree on main issues\" concerning amendments to the [[Constitution of Ukraine]] involving local self-government reform, judicial reform and clear division of authority among President, government and parliament.<ref>[http://www.unian.info/politics/205446-yanukovych-does-not-believe-in-coalition-with-byut.html Yanukovych does not believe in coalition with BYUT], [[UNIAN]] (30 March 2009)</ref> According to Yanukovych, talks with the BYuT were still ongoing in late May 2008.<ref>[http://www.unian.info/politics/225004-party-of-regions-holding-talks-with-byut-yanukovych.html Party of Regions holding talks with BYuT \u2013 Yanukovych], [[UNIAN]] (25 May 2009)</ref>\n\nIn early June talks to build a [[national unity government]] to address the [[2008\u20132009 Ukrainian financial crisis|economic crisis]] collapsed, and Yulia Tymoshenko accused Yanukovych of betrayal: \"He unilaterally, without warning anyone, quit the negotiation process, making a loud political statement, killing the merger and the chances for Ukraine\".<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/09/world/europe/09ukraine.html Ukraine Premier Fails to Form Alliance to Oppose President], [[The New York Times]] (8 June 2009)</ref>\n\nIn September 2009 [[Member of Parliament]] Vasyl Kiselev was expelled from the party and the political council of the Party of Regions. Kiselev was expelled \"for violation of provisions and demands of the charter of the Party of Regions and harming the reputation of the party\".<ref>[http://www.unian.info/politics/266253-lawmaker-kiselev-expelled-from-party-of-regions.html Lawmaker Kiselev expelled from Party of Regions ], [[UNIAN]] (16 September 2009)</ref>\n\nIn September 2009 [[Mykola Azarov]] announced the creation of the [[Anti-Fascist Forum of Ukraine]], the chairmen of which were the member of parliament Dmytro Shentsev ([[Kharkiv]]) and the head of the Luhansk Region State Administration, Valeriy Holenko.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaport.ua/news/society/20072|title=- MediaPort|work=MediaPort|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tsn.ua/ukrayina/azarov-i-dobkin-stvorili-antifashistskii-forum.html|title=\u0410\u0437\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0456 \u0414\u043e\u0431\u043a\u0456\u043d \u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0410\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0444\u0430\u0448\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043e\u0440\u0443\u043c|work=\u0422\u0421\u041d.ua|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Yanukovych presidency===\n{{see also|2010 Ukrainian presidential election}}\n[[File:Trolza 3306.JPG|200px|thumb|Electoral campaign for the Party of Regions says in Russian \"Our Party!\" ([[Kharkiv]], 31 October 2010)]]\nThe Party of Regions endorsed Viktor Yanukovych as their candidate for the [[2010 Ukrainian presidential election|2010 presidential election]].<ref name=\"Yanukovych_president\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukranews.com/eng/article/227204.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120814052702/http://www.ukranews.com/eng/article/227204.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-08-14 |title=Party Of Regions Nominates Yanukovych As Its Presidential Candidate |date=2009-10-23 }}</ref> The party intended to create a new coalition in the [[Verkhovna Rada]] and form a new [[Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine|government]] if Yanukovych won the 2010 presidential elections.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/53618/|title=Regions Party aiming for posts of president and premier|work=[[Kyiv Post]]|date=26 November 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523182522/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/53618/|archivedate=23 May 2012}}</ref> Yanukovych was elected [[President of Ukraine]] on 7 February 2010.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8514517.stm Ukraine: Tymoshenko vows to contest election result], [[BBC News]] (February 15, 2010)</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Rachkevych|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/60468/|title=Yanukovych has yet to secure ruling majority in parliament|work=[[Kyiv Post]]|date=25 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612031750/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/60468/|archivedate=12 June 2012}}</ref> On 19 February the [[Ukrainian parliament]] terminated the powers of Ukrainian [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) Yanukovych, in his place #179 on the electoral list of the Party of Regions at the [[2007 Ukrainian parliamentary election|2007 early parliamentary elections]]. Tamara Yehorenko was registered as an MP by the [[Central Election Commission of Ukraine]] on 26 February.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/60534/|title=CEC registers new MP from Regions Party to replace Yanukovych|work=[[Kyiv Post]]|date=25 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614034603/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/60534/|archivedate=14 June 2012}}</ref> On 3 March Ukrainian President Yanukovych suspended his membership in the Party (Yanukovych was barred by the [[Constitution of Ukraine|Constitution]] from heading a political party)<ref name=newlpor2010>{{cite news|url=http://en.rian.ru/exsoviet/20100423/158710254.html|title=Ukraine's Party of Regions to choose new leader|work=[[RIA Novosti]]|date=23 April 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017165304/http://en.rian.ru/exsoviet/20100423/158710254.html|archivedate=17 October 2012}}</ref> and handed over leadership in the party and in the parliamentary faction to [[Mykola Azarov]].<ref name=Azarovleader/> Nine days later Azarov handed it to Oleksandr Yefremov. On 11 March 2010, together with [[Bloc Lytvyn]] and [[Communist Party of Ukraine]], the party joined the [[first Azarov Government]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/61450/|title=Ukrainian parliament creates new coalition|work=Kyiv Post|date=11 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110212083925/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/61450/|archivedate=12 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe party elected a new Chairman at its 12th congress on 23 April 2010.<ref name=newlpor2010/><ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/64464/ Regions Party to elect new leader at congress on Friday], ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' (20 April 2010) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120926104725/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/64464/ |date=September 26, 2012 }}</ref> [[Prime Minister of Ukraine|Prime Minister]] [[Mykola Azarov]] was elected.<ref name=AzarovLPR23410>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/64876/ Azarov elected Regions Party head], ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' (23 April 2010) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605183156/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/64876/ |date=June 5, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nSeven extra deputies (four [[Bloc Yulia Tymoshenko]] (BYuT) members) joined the Party of Regions faction in October 2010.<ref name=ithaschanged>{{in lang|uk}} [http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/site2/p_fractions \u0414\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0456 \u0444\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0446\u0456\u0457 \u0456 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u043f\u0438 VII \u0441\u043a\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f ''Deputy fractions and Groups VII convocation''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920051907/http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/site2/p_fractions |date=September 20, 2012 }}, Verkhovna Rada</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/50057.html|title=Seven individual MPs join Regions Party faction, Our Ukraine MP joins Lytvyn Bloc|work=Interfax-Ukraine|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> In March 2011 five more former BYuT deputies joined the faction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unian.info/politics/471634-former-byut-members-feldman-yatsenko-and-glus-joined-pr-faction.html|title=Former BYUT members Feldman, Yatsenko and Glus joined PR faction|publisher=|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unian.info/politics/472117-former-byut-members-bagraev-and-pavlenko-joined-pr-faction.html|title=Former BYUT members Bagraev and Pavlenko joined PR faction|publisher=|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> By late November 2012 the Party of Regions faction consisted of 195 lawmakers (20 more than the 175 elected in September 2007).<ref name=DATA/><ref name=ithaschanged/>\n\nDuring the [[2010 Ukrainian local elections]] the party won majorities on most regional and city councils as well as most of the mayoralties (except in western Ukraine), and in the [[2010 Crimean parliamentary election]] (where it won over 70% of the seats).<ref name=\"SvobodawonthankstoYanu\">[http://www.osw.waw.pl/en/publikacje/eastweek/2010-11-04/local-government-elections-ukraine-last-stage-party-regions-takeover- Local government elections in Ukraine: last stage in the Party of Regions\u2019 takeover of power] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813031529/http://www.osw.waw.pl/en/publikacje/eastweek/2010-11-04/local-government-elections-ukraine-last-stage-party-regions-takeover- |date=August 13, 2011 }}, [[Centre for Eastern Studies]] (4 October 2010)</ref> It was the only party that won representatives in all [[Ukrainian Oblasts]] where elections were held, and it won the most votes in all but four of those Oblasts (the four Oblasts where it did not were situated in [[Western Ukraine]]).<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2010/11/8/5552584/ Results of the elections, preliminary data, on interactive maps] by ''[[Ukrayinska Pravda]]'' (8 November 2010)</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, the party was planning to sign a memorandum on cooperation with [[People's Republic of China|China]]'s [[Communist Party of China|Communist Party]].<ref name=\"kyivpost.com\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20100918023341/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/82256 Regions Party planning to sign memorandum on cooperation with Communist Party of China], [[Kyiv Post]] (14 September 2010)</ref>\nOn 14 October 2010, the Party of Regions formed a co-operative arrangement with the [[Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats|Socialists and Democrats]] [[Political groups of the European Parliament|European parliamentary group]].<ref name=\"socialistsanddemocrats.eu\">[http://www.socialistsanddemocrats.eu:80/gpes/public/detail.htm?id=134806&section=NER&category=NEWS Perspectives of good cooperation between S&D and the party of regions of Ukraine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725022506/http://www.socialistsanddemocrats.eu/gpes/public/detail.htm?id=134806&section=NER&category=NEWS |date=2011-07-25 }}, socialistsanddemocrats.eu. 14 Oct 2010. Retrieved 25 Aug 2011.</ref><ref name=\"rferl.org\">{{cite news |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/Ukrainian_Democracy_Will_Be_Built_By_Deeds_Not_Pronouncements/2226856.html/ |title=Ukrainian Democracy Will Be Built By Deeds, Not Pronouncements |first=Taras |last=Kuzio |publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=22 Nov 2010 |accessdate=25 Aug 2011}}</ref>\n\nPresident Yanukovych and the Party of Regions have been accused of trying to create a \"controlled democracy\" in Ukraine and as a means to this of trying to \"destroy\" the main opposition party [[BYuT]], but both have denied these charges.<ref name=Umland>[http://www.opendemocracy.net/od-russia/andreas-umland/ukraine-right-wing-politics-is-genie-out-of-bottle Ukraine right-wing politics: is the genie out of the bottle?], [[openDemocracy.net]] (3 January 2011)</ref><ref name=\"Olszanski\">{{cite web |url=http://www.osw.waw.pl/en/publikacje/osw-commentary/2010-09-29/party-regions-monopolises-power-ukraine |title=The Party of Regions monopolises power in Ukraine |first=Tadeusz A. |last=Olsza\u0144ski |date=29 Sep 2010 |work=OSW Commentary |publisher=[[Centre for Eastern Studies]] (OSW) |accessdate=3 Aug 2011}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-12042561 Ukraine ex-PM Tymoshenko charged with misusing funds], [[BBC News]] (20 December 2010)</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-12171740 Ukraine viewpoint: Novelist Andrey Kurkov], [[BBC News]] (13 January 2011)</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-12219712 Ukraine launches battle against corruption], [[BBC News]] (18 January 2011)</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-11549381 Ukrainians' long wait for prosperity], [[BBC News]] (18 October 2010)</ref><ref>[http://pulitzercenter.org/blog/news-points/ukraine-press-censorship-journalists-uncertain-future Ukraine:Journalists Face Uncertain Future], [[Pulitzer Center on Crisis Reporting]] (27 October 2010)</ref><ref>[http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/108194/yanukovych-tells-u-k-39-s-cameron-no-fears-for-ukraine-39-s-democracy.html Yanukovych Tells U.K's Cameron No Fears for Ukraine's Democracy], ''[[Turkish Weekly]]'' (6 October 2010) {{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>[http://www.partyofregions.org.ua/eng/pr-east-west/4d394880be20c/ Yulia Kovalevska:Only some bankrupt politicians try to use the Day of Unification with the aim of self-PR]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Party of Regions official website (21 January 2011) {{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>[http://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/19116.html President: Ukraine must fulfill its commitments to Council of Europe] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127052632/http://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/19116.html |date=January 27, 2014 }}, [[president.gov.ua]] (13 January 2011)</ref>\n\n====2012 Parliamentary Election results====\n[[File:Ukr elections 2012 multimandate oblasts pr.png|thumb|Results in the 2012 elections]]\nIn August 2011 [[Strong Ukraine]] and [[People's Party (Ukraine)|People's Party]] announced that both parties aimed to merge with the Party of Regions.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/111443 Azarov: We welcome other parties joining Regions Party], [[Kyiv Post]] (23 August 2011) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823132417/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/111443 |date=August 23, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/110925/|title=Azarov: Regions Party teams up with Strong Ukraine|work=[[Kyiv Post]]|date=16 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111201154111/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/110925/|archivedate=1 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=SUmergePoR1>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/115500/ Strong Ukraine postpones decision on merger with Regions Party], [[Kyiv Post]] (22 October 2011) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111022154820/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/115500/ |date=October 22, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=SUmergePoR2>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/115502/ Strong Ukraine to prepare its proposals to Regions Party on posts distribution, says Tigipko], [[Kyiv Post]] (22 October 2011) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111022154749/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/115502/ |date=October 22, 2011 }}</ref> The merger between People's Party and Party of Regions did not materialise.<ref name=nomergePPPoR>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2011/12/12/6831276/ \u041b\u0438\u0442\u0432\u0438\u043d \u043f\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435 \u041d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0443 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0456\u044e \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0438\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0438 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u0443], ''[[Ukrayinska Pravda]]'' (12 December 2011)</ref> Strong Ukraine and Party of Regions merged on 17 March 2012.<ref name=finmergePORSU>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/124603/ Tigipko hooks up with Party of Regions], ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' (20 March 2012)<br />[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/124446 Strong Ukraine party decides on disbanding to join Regions Party], [[Kyiv Post]] (17 March 2012) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320153509/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/124603/ |date=March 20, 2012 }}</ref> (Former) Strong Ukraine leader [[Serhiy Tyhypko]] was unanimously elected Party of Regions deputy chairman and member of the Party of Regions political council the same day.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/124452 Tigipko unanimously elected Regions Party deputy head, political council member], ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' (17 March 2012) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318041822/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/124452 |date=March 18, 2012 }}</ref> Party of Regions [[People's Deputy of Ukraine|parliamentarian]] [[Olena Bondarenko (Party of Regions politician)|Olena Bondarenko]] had stated (early March 2012) that Party of Regions, Strong Ukraine party and \"another party\" planned to hold a unity congress on 17 March 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/123737/|title=Lawmaker: Party of Regions to merge with two other parties on 17 March|work=[[Kyiv Post]]|date=6 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306234921/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/123737/|archivedate=6 March 2012}}</ref> No additional third party merged with the Party of Regions on 17 March 2012; according to Ukrainian media Tyhypko had personally prevented a merger of [[United Centre]] with the Party of Regions in March 2012.<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2012/03/15/6960715/ \u0422\u0456\u0433\u0456\u043f\u043a\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0436\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0432 \u0432\u0456\u0434 \"\u0420\u0435\u0433\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0456\u0432\" \u043d\u0435 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438 \u0411\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0443], ''[[Ukrayinska Pravda]]'' (15 March 2012)</ref>\n\nIn October 2011 a cooperation agreement was signed in [[Astana]] between the [[Kazakhstan]]i [[Nur Otan]] and the Party of Regions.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/regions-party-to-cooperate-with-ruling-party-in-ka-117518.html Regions Party to cooperate with ruling party in Kazakhstan], [[Kyiv Post]] (24 November 2011)</ref>\n\nIn late 2011, the party's popularity dropped in opinion polls below 20%, mainly because the party was losing votes to the [[Communist Party of Ukraine]].<ref>[http://www.ratinggroup.com.ua/en/products/politic/data/entry/13981/ Electoral moods of the population of Ukraine: December 2011], [[Sociological group \"RATING\"|Rating]] (20 December 2011)</ref><ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/118551 Poll: Batkivschyna Party's electoral rating tops Regions Party in Ukraine], ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' (9 December 2011) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111216201603/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/118551 |date=December 16, 2011 }}</ref><ref>[http://ratinggroup.com.ua/en/cardiogram/parties/ Ratings of parties], [[Sociological group \"RATING\"]]<br />[http://ratinggroup.com.ua/en/products/politic/data/entry/13990/ Electoral moods of the Ukrainian population: February 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129225011/http://ratinggroup.com.ua/en/products/politic/data/entry/13990/ |date=2014-11-29 }}, [[Sociological group \"RATING\"]] (5 March 2012)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://razumkov.org.ua/eng/poll.php?poll_id=115|title=Ukraine, poll: If parliamentary elections were held next Sunday how would you vote? (recurrent, 2010-2013) // Razumkov Centre|author=Sparkle Design Studio|accessdate=16 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304042611/http://razumkov.org.ua/eng/poll.php?poll_id=115|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2012, the top PR consultancy [[Burson-Marsteller]] was hired to represent the interests of the Party of Regions, \"to help them communicate its activities as the governing party of Ukraine, as well as to help it explain better its position on the [[Yulia Tymoshenko]] case\", as explained by Robert Mack, a senior manager at Burson-Marsteller.<ref name=euobserver>[http://euobserver.com/24/116076 EU Observer], 27 April 2012</ref>\n\nIn the [[2012 Ukrainian parliamentary election|October 2012 parliamentary elections]] the party won 72 seats and 30% of the votes under [[party-list proportional representation]] (falling from 34% in [[2007 Ukrainian parliamentary election|2007]] and 32% in [[2006 Ukrainian parliamentary election|2006]])<ref>[http://ukrainianweek.com/Politics/64047 The Distorted Will of the People], ''[[The Ukrainian Week]]'' (5 November 2012)</ref> and another 115 by winning 115 simple-majority constituencies (it had competed in 204 of the 225 constituencies);<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://apk.rbc.ua/ukr/vyboru2012/party/p01/okrug Candidates], [[RBC Ukraine]]</ref> this sum gave them a total of 187 seats and 41,56% of the 450 seats in the [[Ukrainian Parliament]].<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.cvk.gov.ua/vnd2012/wp300pt001f01=900.html Proportional votes]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030000000/http://www.cvk.gov.ua/vnd2012/wp300pt001f01%3D900.html |date=October 30, 2012 }} & [http://www.cvk.gov.ua/vnd2012/wp039pt001f01=900.html Constituency seats]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105073259/http://www.cvk.gov.ua/vnd2012/wp039pt001f01%3D900.html |date=November 5, 2012 }}, [[Central Electoral Commission of Ukraine]]<br />[http://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2012/10/29/6975859/ % of total seats], ''[[Ukrayinska Pravda]]''</ref> The party had lost about 2 million voters compared with the [[2007 Ukrainian parliamentary election|previous election]].<ref name=\"CESOlsza\u0144skiUKel12\">[http://www.osw.waw.pl/en/publikacje/analyses/2012-11-07/after-parliamentary-elections-ukraine-a-tough-victory-party-regions After the parliamentary elections in Ukraine: a tough victory for the Party of Regions], [[Centre for Eastern Studies]] (7 November 2012)</ref> On 12 December 2012 the party formed a [[parliamentary faction]] of 210 deputies.<ref name=\"PRmakes185210\"/> On 31 December 2013 this faction was 204 votes strong.<ref name=ithaschanged/>\n\nAt least 18 Party of Regions deputies have criminal ties, according to [[Hennadiy Moskal]], deputy head of Parliament's Committee on Organized Crime and Corruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/Analysis/Outside-View/2014/02/14/Viktor-Yanukovych-From-partner-to-violent-kleptocrat/UPI-74961392386437/|title=Outside View: Viktor Yanukovych: From partner to violent kleptocrat|work=UPI|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, 148 [[People's Deputy of Ukraine|people's deputies of Ukraine]] signed a letter to the [[Polish Sejm]] asking to recognize the [[Volhynian tragedy]] as a genocide ([[:uk:\u0417\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u0434\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0456\u0432 \u0432\u0456\u0434 \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0456\u0457 \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0456\u0432 \u0456 \u041a\u041f\u0423 \u0434\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0421\u0435\u0439\u043c\u0443]]). A total of 119 of those parliamentarians were members of Party of Regions, while other 23 were from the [[Communist Party of Ukraine]].\n\n===Post-Yanukovych presidency===\n\n====Yanukovych impeachment====\nOn 22 February 2014, during the \"[[2014 Ukrainian revolution|Maidan revolution]]\", the Verkhovna Rada voted to impeach the honorary chairman of the party, Viktor Yanukovych, as President of Ukraine.<ref name=\"Yanuousted\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-26312008 Ukraine: Speaker Oleksandr Turchynov named interim president], [[BBC News]] (23 February 2014)<br />[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-26248275 Ukraine protests timeline], [[BBC News]] (23 February 2014)</ref> Out of the 38 PoR deputies present, 36 voted in favor of ousting Yanukovych, while two did not take part in the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/radan_gs09/ns_golos?g_id=3863 |script-title=uk:\u041f\u043e\u0456\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442 \u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0443\u0441\u0443\u043d\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u0432\u0456\u0434 \u0432\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0436\u0435\u043d\u044c (\u21164193) - \u0437\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0443 \u0442\u0430 \u0432 \u0446\u0456\u043b\u043e\u043c\u0443 |trans-title=Roll-call vote on the draft resolution on the withdrawal of the President of Ukraine from fulfilling constitutional obligations (\u21164193) - as the primary and on the whole |language=uk |publisher=Parliament of Ukraine |date=22 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140312210622/http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/radan_gs09/ns_golos?g_id=3863 |archivedate=March 12, 2014 }}</ref> Simultaneously both Yanukovych and former Prime Minister [[Mykola Azarov]] fled to [[Russia]].<ref name=AzYaPorftR/>\n\nIn a written statement the next day, the party denounced Yanukovych, stating they \"strongly condemn the criminal orders that led to human victims, an empty state treasury, huge debts, shame before the eyes of the Ukrainian people and the entire world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/where-is-viktor-yanukovych-337418.html|title=Where is Viktor Yanukovych? (VIDEO, UPDATE)|work=KyivPost|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nLate January 2014 the party's symbol and activities were banned in the [[Chernivtsi oblast|Chernivtsi]],{{citation needed|date=February 2014}} [[Ternopil oblast|Ternopil]] and [[Ivano-Frankivsk oblast|Ivano-Frankivsk]] regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/party-of-regions-communist-party-banned-in-ivano-frankivsk-and-ternopil-regions-335655.html|title=Party of Regions, Communist Party banned in Ivano-Frankivsk and Ternopil regions|work=KyivPost|date=27 January 2014|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/261093.html|title=Ivano-Frankivsk Regional Council bans activities of Communist Party, Regions Party, Opposition Bloc, Ukraine Development Party|agency=Interfax-Ukraine|date=17 April 2015|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> Although there was no legal basis for these bans since in Ukraine only a court can ban the activities of a political force.<ref>[http://ukrainianweek.com/Politics/136670 Dangerous Liaisons], [[The Ukrainian Week]] (18 May 2015)</ref>\n\nThe Party of Regions faction in [[Zhytomyr]] announced its dissolution on 19 February 2014, in connection with the crisis of the preceding three months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://obozrevatel.com/politics/80561-zhitomirskie-regionalyi-samoraspustilis.htm|title=\u0416\u0438\u0442\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044b \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c|work=\u041e\u0431\u043e\u0437\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 2014 faction leader [[Oleksandr Yefremov]] declared that the party was moving into the opposition.<ref name=PoRdKP/> 77 of its MPs had left the faction over the past few days.<ref name=PoRdKP>[https://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/party-of-regions-faction-becomes-opposition-337488.html Party of Regions faction becomes opposition], [[Kyiv Post]] (24 February 2014)</ref>\n\nOn 25 February 2014 [[Anatoliy Kinakh]] and 32 other mostly former PoR deputies created the parliamentary faction [[Economic Development (parliamentary faction)|Economic Development]].<ref name=ithaschanged/><ref name=EDRU25214>[http://www.nrcu.gov.ua/en/148/557077/ Rada creates Group for Economic Development] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140530045305/http://www.nrcu.gov.ua/en/148/557077/ |date=May 30, 2014 }}, [[Radio Ukraine]] (25 February 2014)</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2014 Yanukovych asked the Party of Regions to exclude him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euronews.com/2014/03/28/ousted-leader-yanukovych-calls-for-referendum-in-every-region-of-ukraine/|title=Ousted leader Yanukovych calls for referendum in every region of Ukraine|work=euronews|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> The next day, at a party congress, the party nominated [[Mykhailo Dobkin]] as its presidential candidate for the [[2014 Ukrainian presidential election]].<ref name=7414expfPoR/> The congress expelled from the party Yanukovych, Azarov, former First Deputy Prime Minister [[Serhiy Arbuzov]], ex-chairman of the Ministry of Revenue and Duties [[Oleksandr Viktorovych Klymenko|Olexander Klimenko]], former Energy Minister [[Eduard Stavitskyi]], ex-governor of the Donetsk region [[Andrew Shishatskiy]] and [[Valery Konovalyuk]].<ref name=EnlargedBPoR/>\n\nOn 7 April 2014 the political council of the party expelled [[Sergiy Tigipko]], [[Oleh Tsariov]] and [[Yuriy Boiko]] from the party.<ref name=7414expfPoR>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/199490.html Ukraine's Party of Regions expels presidential hopefuls Tigipko, Tsariov and Boiko], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (7 April 2014)</ref>\n\n[[Mykhailo Dobkin]] was the PoR's candidate in the [[2014 Ukrainian presidential election|snap presidential election of 25 May 2014]], tallying only 3 percent of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrcu.gov.ua/en/148/566632/ |title=Poroshenko wins presidential election with 54.7% of vote - CEC |publisher=[[Radio Ukraine International]] |date=29 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529212731/http://www.nrcu.gov.ua/en/148/566632/ |archivedate=29 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn 3 June 2014 twenty PoR deputies left the party's parliamentary faction.<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/207746.html 20 MPs leave Regions Party faction], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (3 June 2014)</ref> Thus the faction's strength was reduced from (at its highest point on 12 December 2012) 210 deputies to 80 deputies on 6 June 2014.<ref name=\"PRmakes185210\"/><ref name=\"20quitPoR3614\">[http://tass.ru/en/world/734551 20 lawmakers quit Party of Regions faction in Ukrainian parliament], [[ITAR-TASS]] (3 June 2014)</ref><ref name=ithaschanged/> A by-product of this was that it became the second biggest faction in parliament, after the faction of [[Batkivshchyna]] with 85 members.<ref name=ithaschanged/> On 2 July 2014 the 32 member strong new parliamentary faction [[For Peace and Stability (parliamentary faction)|For Peace and Stability]], composed mostly of former Party of Regions MPs, was formed.<ref name=FPiSUP2714>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/07/2/7030718/ ], [[Ukrayinska Pravda]] (2 July 2014)</ref><ref name=DynfPiS>{{in lang|uk}} [http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/site2/p_fraction_dep_changes?pidid=2601 ''Dynamics in the fraction For Peace and Stability in the VII convocation''], [[Verkhovna Rada]]</ref>\n\n====Criminal case against deputies====\nOn September 17, 2014, amidst the ongoing [[war in Donbass]], a group of 24 [[People's Deputy of Ukraine|people's deputies of Ukraine]] from the Party of Regions and the [[Communist Party of Ukraine]], who are members of the Ukrainian parliamentary group [[For Peace and Stability]], met with [[Sergei Naryshkin]], the [[Chairman of the State Duma|chairman]] of the [[Russian Federation|Russian]] [[State Duma]].<ref>[http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/09/18/7038181/ It became known &#91;Ukrainian&#93; deputies who in Russia \"stand for the interest of the Russian World\"]. [[Ukrayinska Pravda]]. 18 September 2014</ref> On September 25, 2014, the Central Investigation Administration of the Ukrainian [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Ukraine)|Ministry of Internal Affairs]] opened a criminal case against those deputies charging them with infringement on the territorial integrity of Ukraine.<ref>[http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/09/25/7038936/ MVS opened a criminal case for the voyage of deputies to the State Duma]. [[Ukrayinska Pravda]]. 25 September 2014</ref>\n\n====2014 Parliamentary Election and disintegration====\nOn 14 September 2014 Party of Regions chose not to participate in the [[2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election|2014 parliamentary elections]]; the party deemed the election as lacking legitimacy because the residents of the [[Donbass]] could not vote in the election.<ref name=\"en.ria.ru\"/><ref name=OBBBCU/> Many individual members of Party of Regions ended up as candidates of [[Opposition Bloc]].<ref name=FPoR23914>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/225005.html Opposition Bloc chooses top ten candidates for parliamentary elections], [[Interfax Ukraine]] (23 September 2014)<br />[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/allies-of-yanukovych-trying-for-parliament-365185.html?flavour=mobile Allies of Yanukovych trying for parliament], [[Kyiv Post]] (21 September 2014)<br />[http://un.ua/eng/article/532653.html Party Of Regions Will Not Contest Snap Parliamentary Elections Independently], [[Ukrainian News Agency]] (14 September 2014) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924041429/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/225005.html |date=September 24, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=OBBBCU/>\n\nBy the summer of 2015 most representatives of the party in 2014 were members of Opposition Bloc, [[Revival (Ukraine)|Revival]] or [[Our Land (Ukraine)|Our Land]].<ref name=Rs15BBCU/> Others continued their political careers in other parties (mostly [[Petro Poroshenko Bloc]]);<ref name=\"potoibppd23okt15\"/> according to Ukrainian media research of February 2016 22% of the Petro Poroshenko Bloc representatives in regional councils and 12% of this party parliamentary deputies were former members of the Party of Regions.<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2016/02/7/7098140/ Media: the BPP 22% of the members of regional councils and 12% of MPs - ex- \"Regions\"], [[Ukrayinska Pravda]] (February 7, 2016)</ref>\n\n==Party's electoral results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ [[Verkhovna Rada]]\n!rowspan=2|<center>'''Year</center>\n!colspan=3|<center>'''Party-list'''</center>\n!rowspan=2|<center>'''Constituency <small>/total</small>'''</center>\n!rowspan=2|<center>'''Overall seats won</center>\n!rowspan=2|<center>'''Seat change</center>\n! rowspan=2| '''Government\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n|<center>'''Popular vote'''</center>\n|<center>'''%'''</center>\n|<center>'''Seats <small>/total</small>'''</center>\n|-\n! [[1998 Ukrainian parliamentary election|1998]]\n| 241,262\n| 0.9%\n| 0/225\n| 2/225\n| {{Composition bar|2|450|hex={{Party of Regions/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 2\n| {{partial|minority support}}\n|-\n! [[2002 Ukrainian parliamentary election|2002]]\n| colspan=2|[[For United Ukraine]] bloc\n| 6/225\n| 25/225\n| {{Composition bar|31|450|hex={{Party of Regions/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 29\n| {{yes|coalition government}}\n|-\n! [[2006 Ukrainian parliamentary election|2006]]\n| 8,148,745\n| 32.14%\n| 186/450\n| N/A\n| {{Composition bar|186|450|hex={{Party of Regions/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 155\n| {{yes|coalition government}}\n|-\n! [[2007 Ukrainian parliamentary election|2007]]\n| 8,013,895\n| 34.37%\n| 175/450\n| N/A\n| {{Composition bar|175|450|hex={{Party of Regions/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}} 11\n| {{no|opposition}}\n|-\n! [[2012 Ukrainian parliamentary election|2012]]\n| 6,116,815\n| 30.00%\n| 72/225\n| 113/225\n| {{Composition bar|185|450|hex={{Party of Regions/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 10\n| {{yes|government}}\n|-\n! [[2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election|2014]]\n| No participation\n| 0%\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{Composition bar|0|450|hex={{Party of Regions/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}} 185\n| {{no|extra parliamentary}}\n|}\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n| colspan=7|[[President of Ukraine|Presidency of Ukraine]]\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Election year\n!rowspan=2|Candidate\n!colspan=2|First Round\n!colspan=2|Second Round\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Result\n|-\n! # of<br />overall votes\n! % of<br />overall vote\n! # of<br />overall votes\n! % of<br />overall vote\n|-\n! [[1999 Ukrainian presidential election|1999]]\n| [[Leonid Kuchma]]\n| 9,598,672\n| 38.0\n| 15,870,722\n| 57.7\n| {{yes|Won}}\n|-\n! [[2004 Ukrainian presidential election|2004]]\n| [[Viktor Yanukovych]]\n| 11,008,731\n| 39.3\n| 12,848,528\n| 44.2\n| {{no|Lost}}\n|-\n! [[2010 Ukrainian presidential election|2010]]\n| [[Viktor Yanukovych]]\n| 8,686,642\n| 35.3\n| 12,481,266\n| 49.0\n| {{yes|Won}}\n|-\n! [[2014 Ukrainian presidential election|2014]]\n| [[Mykhailo Dobkin]]\n| 546,138\n| 3.0\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\"|\n| {{no|Lost}}\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Date !! Party leader !! Remarks\n|-\n| 1997\u20132001 || [[Volodymyr Vasylyovych Rybak|Volodymyr Rybak]] ||\n|-\n| 2001\u20132002 || [[Mykola Azarov]] ||\n|-\n| 2002\u20132003 || [[Volodymyr Semynozhenko]] ||\n|-\n| 2003\u20132010 || [[Viktor Yanukovych]] || \n|-\n| 2010\u20132014 || [[Mykola Azarov]] || \n|-\n| 2014\u2013''present'' || [[Borys Kolesnikov]] ||\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\nIn 2012  [[Taras Kuzio]] claimed the electorate of the party was very loyal to them.<ref name=\"KuzioPORvotersdontgoaway\">[http://www.jamestown.org/single/?no_cache=1&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=39981 Eight Reasons Why Ukraine\u2019s Party of Regions Will Win the 2012 Elections] by [[Taras Kuzio]], [[The Jamestown Foundation]] (17 October 2012)<br />[http://www.taraskuzio.net/media20_files/8.pdf UKRAINE: Yushchenko needs Tymoshenko as ally again] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515074305/http://www.taraskuzio.net/media20_files/8.pdf |date=2013-05-15 }} by [[Taras Kuzio]], [[Oxford Analytica]] (5 October 2007)</ref> According to a poll by the Kyiv International Sociology Institute, the number of voters ready to go to polling stations to vote for the Party of Regions dropped from 38% in June 2010 to 13.9% in April 2011.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/103085/ Poll: Party of Regions of Ukraine losing support], ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' (April 28, 2011) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128071533/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/103085/ |date=January 28, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Recent issue stances==\n{{Update section|date=March 2020}}\nThe party asserts it has a pragmatic approach to [[Ukrainian EU membership]] with respect to the country's foreign economic interests; it supports \"to walk the path of European integration and the implementation of respective standards in the social and economic spheres\". Yet, given the European financial crisis, the party sees the issue of Ukraine's accession to the EU as \"purely theoretical.\"<ref name=\"purely theoretical\">[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/119031 Regions Party: Question of Ukraine's EU membership now 'purely theoretical'], [[Kyiv Post]] (15 December 2011) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111216014907/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/119031 |date=December 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe party accepts [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] as the only [[state language]] in Ukraine, but also claims to promote \"both the development of the state Ukrainian language and languages of other nationalities residing on the territory of Ukraine\".<ref>[http://www.partyofregions.org.ua/en/deputy_faction/activities/show/1767 Yuriy Miroshnychenko: Viktor Yanukovych promotes the comprehensive development and use of the official language], Official Information Server of the party (21 February 2011) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527051214/http://www.partyofregions.org.ua/en/deputy_faction/activities/show/1767 |date=May 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.partyofregions.org.ua/en/deputy_faction/activities/show/1763 Volodymyr Zubanov: The current government promotes the development of the languages of all people in Ukraine], Official Information Server of the party (21 February 2011) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527051232/http://www.partyofregions.org.ua/en/deputy_faction/activities/show/1763 |date=May 27, 2012 }}</ref>{{third-party-inline|date=December 2011}}\n\nThe Party of Regions supports the cancellation of a number of [[Verkhovna Rada#Deputies|benefits for deputies]] of the [[Ukrainian parliament]].<ref>[http://www.partyofregions.org.ua/en/news/top/show/6992 Olexander Yefremov: The Party of Regions supports cancellation of a number of benefits for MPs] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530225409/http://www.partyofregions.org.ua/en/news/top/show/6992 |date=2012-05-30 }}, Official Information Server of the party (5 December 2011)<br />[http://www.interfax.co.uk/ukraine-news/yefremov-says-party-of-regions-ready-to-vote-for-cancelation-of-parliamentary-immunity/ Yefremov says Party of Regions ready to vote for cancelation of parliamentary immunity], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (15 April 2013)</ref> Leading party members have stated the party \"would mercilessly expel [[corruption in Ukraine|corrupt]] officials from its ranks\".<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/123533/ Kliuyev:Corruption a key reason for delay in reforms in Ukraine], [[Kyiv Post]] (2 March 2012) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302220359/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/123533/ |date=March 2, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013 Party of Regions [[Verkhovna Rada|MP]] [[Oleh Tsariov]] demanded a criminal investigation into the activities of [[United States Department of State]] lead [[Office of eDiplomacy#Major Programs of the Office of eDiplomacy|TechCamp]] in [[Ukraine]] because he believed it was engaged in \"preparations for inciting a [[civil war]]\" because during training \"instructors share their experience of Internet technologies, which are aimed at shaping public opinion and enhancing the protest potential and which were used to organize street protests in Libya, Egypt, Tunisia and Syria\".<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/175839.html Party of Regions MP Tsariov accuses US Embassy in Ukraine of training revolutionaries for street protests], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (20 November 2013)</ref>\n\nThe Party of Regions has lost much of its influence amid the ongoing [[Ukrainian Revolution of 2014|crisis]] in Ukraine. 72 deputies<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gazeta.ua/ru/articles/politics/_esche-troe-deputatov-vyshli-iz-partii-regionov-v-summe-uzhe-72/543739|title=\u0415\u0449\u0435 \u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0432\u044b\u0448\u043b\u0438 \u0438\u0437 \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u043c\u043c\u0435 \u0443\u0436\u0435 72|work=Gazeta.ua|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> have left the party, and remaining deputies either supported key opposition demands like impeaching Yanukovich, firing Zakharchenko and the General Prosecutor or did not vote.\n\nOn 23 February, the party faction of Verkhovna Rada published a statement blaming everything wrong on \u2033Yanukovych and his inner circle\u2033, accusing him in particular of giving out \u2033criminal orders\u2033 and lamenting that the whole party had been \u2033in effect hostage of one corrupt Family\u2033.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://interfax.com.ua/news/political/192177.html|title=\u041e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u043e\u0431\u044b\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u043b\u0435\u0436\u0438\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u042f\u043d\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u0435 \u0438 \u0435\u0433\u043e \u0431\u043b\u0438\u0436\u0430\u0439\u0448\u0435\u043c \u043e\u043a\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u2013 \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0444\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432|work=\u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0444\u0430\u043a\u0441-\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0430|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April 2014 the party presented its new economic doctrine that consisted of minimal taxes and fees, maximum investor protection, increasing investment attractiveness, as well as deregulation and simplification of licensing procedures, the establishment of a transparent tax system and tax cuts (a reduction of income tax to 12.5%, reducing the income tax rate to 14%), decreasing the inspections of small and medium-sized businesses to not more than once in 5 years, maintaining a 15-year preferential tax system in agriculture, the introduction of effective direct subsidies to farmers to compete on the world market, a compensation of 50% of new fixed assets in crop and livestock in creation of new industries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sq.com.ua/rus/news/politika/07.04.2014/partiya_regionov_prezentovala_novuyu_ekonomicheskuyu_doktrinu|title=\u041f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0443\u044e \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0443|author=\u041d\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u044c\u044f \u041a\u043e\u0431\u0437\u0430\u0440|date=7 April 2014|work=Status Quo|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Political program===\n{{Primary sources|section|date=February 2014}}\n\n====European integration====\nOn the question of European integration, different views exist within the party. On the one hand, President [[Viktor Yanukovych]], who is a member of the party, has repeatedly underlined his pro-European stances.<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/180734.html Ukraine's course for European integration remains the same, repeats president] & [http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/180780.html Ukraine will decide on conditions of signing agreement with EU before March summit - Yanukovych], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (10 December 2013)<br />[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/180778.html Yanukovych orders government to analyze economic risks of partnership treaty with EU by March], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (10 December 2013)</ref><ref name=\"purely theoretical\"/> On the other hand, experts have described the Party of Regions as [[Euroscepticism|eurosceptic]].<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.opendemocracy.net/od-russia/andreas-umland/ukraine-right-wing-politics-is-genie-out-of-bottle Ukraine right-wing politics: is the genie out of the bottle?], [[openDemocracy.net]] (January 3, 2011)</ref><ref name=EWparties>[https://books.google.com/books?id=H23Pv4Ik3vMC&pg=PA396 Communist and Post-Communist Parties in Europe] by [[Uwe Backes]] and [[Patrick Moreau]], [[Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht]], 2008, {{ISBN|978-3525369128}} (page 396)</ref> The Party's official stance is for increased European integration, but within a framework that is favorable to Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://partyofregions.ua/news/event/5298bd7fc4ca42ca7a0000aa|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202105008/http://partyofregions.ua/news/event/5298bd7fc4ca42ca7a0000aa|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 December 2013|title=\"\u0415\u0421 \u2013 \u0434\u0430, \u0441\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0449\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044e \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0447\u0438\u0445 \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442 \u2013 \u043d\u0435\u0442\": \u043c\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0433 \u041f\u0410\u0420\u0422\u0418\u0418 \u0420\u0415\u0413\u0418\u041e\u041d\u041e\u0412 \u043d\u0430 \u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u0438|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Domestic policy====\n{{Unreferenced section|date = July 2015}}\n[[File:\u0414\u0435\u043d\u044c \u041f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0434\u044b \u0432 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0435, 2010 104.JPG|thumb|200px|alt=Blue flags at a demonstration|Party of Regions flags in [[Donetsk]], 2010]]\nThe party supports affordable housing through state mortgages with a 3% [[annual percentage rate]], social contracts with employers, financial aid for newborns (to be doubled in 2017), perinatal centers in each region and the upgrading of [[maternity home]]s.\n\nThe party supports at least 75-percent placement in higher-educational institutions, a minimum-wage student stipend, a minimum 20-percent annual raise in educator salaries and universal Internet access. In labor, the party supports fully subsidizing employers of the disabled, orphans, single mothers and workers over age 50; training the unemployed for occupations with labor shortages; providing internships to students; giving young professionals their first job, and a median salary of [[Ukrainian hryvnia|\u20b4]]8,000 by 2017.\n\nThe party supports a median salary of \u20b48,000 for physicians and \u20b45,500 for other medical personnel, reducing basic-medicine prices by 30 percent, providing access to medicines to patients with cancer, heart disease, tuberculosis and [[HIV/AIDS]], mobile medical facilities in all rural areas, treatment and rehabilitation for people with limited physical abilities and new pools, stadiums, ice arenas and sports fields in all regions.\n\nThe party supports comfortable, affordable housing; security for senior citizens; the repayment of all deposits in the Sberbank of the USSR up to \u20b45,000 by 2017; a minimum pension 20 percent over the [[poverty threshold]], and significant pension increases for military and law-enforcement personnel. In the environmental sector, the party supports the completion of the Shelter Project for the [[Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant]] by 2015, the installation of 20,000 centralized water-purification systems and recycling plants in each region.\n\n====National economy====\n* Modern economy\n** Main goals: GDP growth (at least 5% annually), stability of national currency\n** Implementation through: gradual reduction of corporate income tax (16% before 2014), introduction of tax holidays for IT and innovation projects for period of 10 years, providing domestic manufacturers with affordable bank loans\n* Effective power generation, energy independence\n** increase the extraction of domestic coal, oil and [[shale gas]]\n** begin developing the shelf gas fields\n** enhance the use of solar, wind and hydropower\n** modernizing power plants for efficient use of domestic coal and other fuels\n* Rural policy\n** creation of 1,500 agricultural cooperatives\n** construction of new elevators, vegetable and fruit storage\n** establishing prices for land share (no less than 20,000 hrv/ha) and rent (no lower than 1,000 hrv/ha)\n** development of social infrastructure in rural areas (auto roads, hospitals and schools, gas supply)\n* Infrastructure policy\n** construction of modern automobile roads (with ability to travel from west to east of Ukraine in 14 hours)\n** new speed rail link between the capital and regions\n** affordable aviation transportation for each Ukrainian\n** construction and redevelopment of airports, sea and river ports, rail stations\n** construction of new metro stations and development of commuter transportation\n\n====Government and society====\n'''Effective nation: responsible government and open society'''\n* Civil policy\n** intellectual freedom\n** freedom of speech\n** equal opportunities for women and men in all spheres of life\n** legislative support for the native language\n** granting to the [[Russian language]] the status of the second state language\n* Regional policy\n** increased role of local government\n** 60% of consolidated state budget to local councils\n* Law enforcement and military policy\n** contract army\n** abolition of compulsory conscription from January 1, 2014\n* Foreign policy\n** preservation of the non-aligned status of Ukraine \u2013 safety guarantee for every citizen\n** gaining associate membership in the [[European Union]], creation of free-trade zone, removal of visa barriers between Ukraine and the EU\n** strengthening economic cooperation within the free-trade zone framework with countries of the [[Commonwealth of Independent States]]\n** strategic partnership with Russia, United States, China\n** opening to Ukraine the markets of \"[[Big Twenty]]\" and of developing countries\n** realization of competitive advantages of the country for the right to host sporting and cultural events at European and world levels\n\n==Selected members==\n* [[Mykola Azarov]] \u2013 Chairman\n* [[Oleksandr Yefremov]] \u2013 Deputy Chairman of the Party of Regions on Relations with the Parliament of Ukraine\n* [[Petro Pysarchuk]]\n\n==''Vremya Regionov''==\nThe Party of Regions publishes a [[Ukraine|nationwide]] [[newspaper]] called ''\u0412\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f \u0420\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432'' (English trans. ''Time of the Regions''). The newspaper is based and published in [[Kiev]]. It is released weekly, every Thursday, in [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] and [[Russian language|Russian]]. The newspaper was launched on 24 August 2008. It is available [https://web.archive.org/web/20100621193322/http://www.partyofregions.org.ua/42691596bc139/4c176b692b7fc/ online] in [[Portable Document Format|PDF]] format.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Viktor Yanukovych]]\n* [[Rinat Akhmetov]]\n* [[Yevhen Kushnaryov]]\n* [[Alliance of National Unity]]\n* [[2006 Ukrainian political crisis]]\n* [[2007 Ukrainian political crisis]]\n* [[2008 Ukrainian political crisis]]\n* [[Politics of Ukraine]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{in lang|ru|en}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20131213040153/http://partyofregions.ua/ Official web site of the party]\n<!--*[http://www.regions.org.ua/ Official web site of parliamentary faction \"Regions of Ukraine\"] redirection to http://www.partyofregions.org.ua/-->\n*{{in lang|uk}} [https://archive.is/20120314111143/http://www.mv2010.org.ua/ Press-center of the central staff on local elections]\n*{{in lang|ru}} [http://www.mo-re.org/ Official website of the youth wing of Party of Regions]\n*{{in lang|ru}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20100621193322/http://www.partyofregions.org.ua/42691596bc139/4c176b692b7fc/ Vremya Regionov]\n{{Ukrainian Political Parties}}\n{{Crimean political parties}}\n{{Euromaidan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Party Of Regions}}\n[[Category:Party of Regions| ]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Centrist parties in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Euromaidan]]\n[[Category:Eurosceptic parties in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary factions in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Regionalist parties in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Russian political parties in Ukraine]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "link maintenance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Party_of_Regions"}
{"title_page": "Conservative.bg", "text_new": "{{Other uses|\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044a|\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044a (\u043f\u043e\u044f\u0441\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435)}}{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = Conservative.bg\n| logo = \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044a-\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e.png\n| publisher = Conservativebg LTD\n| depeditor = Mihail Krustev\n| political = conservative\n| language = Bulgarian\n| chiefeditor = Nikolay Oblakoff\n| website = conservative.bg\n}}'''\"Conservative.bg'\"''' is a Bulgarian online platform for opinions, analyzes and comments with a right-wing conservative focus and emphasis on political, social and cultural topics.\n\nInitially, the platform was founded in 2017 under the name '''\"Misal\"''' (\"Thought\" in bulgarian) but after a merger with another media '''\"The Five Corners\"''' in 2018\u00a0 is renamed to the '''\"Conservative.bg\"'''.\n\n== Conservative.bg right-wing platform ==\nRight-wing platform '''\"Conservative.bg\"''' offers free access to all of its content, as well as to its annual review edition. The media was founded in 2017 in order to be an Internet portal for opinions and analyzes from a right conservative perspective.\n\nThe site founders are Nikolay Oblakoff, Mihail Krastev, Boyan Zlatanov, Emil Vulkov, Simeon Popov and Teodor Dimokenchev. All of them remain editors to this day. Popular columnists include Krystian Szkwarek, Dimitar Petrov, Toncho Kraevski, Ivan Stambolov - Sula, Toma Petrov, Dimitar Vuchev, Boris Stanimirov and Nikola Filipov.\n\nGuest authors on the platform are popular names in political, social and cultural life, such as Martin Tabakov, Petar Nikolov, Lyubomir Kanov, [[Angel Dzhambazki]], Kuzman Iliev , Toma Bikov, [[Andrey Novakov]], Vladimir Sirkarov, Alex Alexiev, Villy Lilkov and others.\n\nIn addition to the website and the annual review edition, '''\"Conservative.bg\"''' platform also organizes public discussions on social and political topics. Among the participants of these events are Ognian Minchev, Haralan Alexandrov, [[Ryszard Legutko]], Dimitar Stoyanovich, Boyan Rashev, Krasen Stanchev, [[Boyko Vasilev|Boyko Vasilev,]] Neno Dimov and others.\n\n== \u0412\u044a\u043d\u0448\u043d\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0438 ==\n'''\"Conservative.bg\"''' platform is the successor to the '''\"Misal\"''' platform, created through its merger with another online media '''\"The Five Corners\"'''. The platform uses the domain of the related to it Conservative Youth Club.\n\nThe first issue of '''\"YearBook\"''' is published in 2018.\n\nSince 10.07.2019 '''\"Conservative.bg\"''' is a registered trademark within the European Union with number 00106021.\n\n== Sections ==\n'''\"Politics\"''' - political analyzes from Bulgaria and the world\n\n'''\"Society\"''' - community and social topics\n\n'''\"Libertarian\"''' - economical and financial analysis\n\n'''\"Thought\"''' - views on culture and science\n\n'''\"On This Day\"''' - a historical overview\n\n== Editorial staff ==\n'''Editor-in-chief''' - Nikolay Oblakov\n\n'''Deputy editor''' - Mihail Krastev\n\n'''Editorial Board''' - Boyan Zlatanov, Teodor Dimokenchev, Nikola Bushnyakov, Emil Valkov, Simeon Popov, Leda Necheva, Ivo Georgiev, Toma Petrov\n\n'''Columnists''' - Nikola Filipov, Victoria Georgieva, Krystian Szkwarek, Toncho Kraevski, Dimitar Petrov, Svetoslav Alexandrov, Boris Stanimirov, Martin Tabakov, Lachezar Tomov, Stefan Stoyanov, Christian Anadoliev, Dimitar Vuchev, Ivan Stambolov - Sula, Vladislav Apostolov, Georgi Zayakov\n\n== YearBook ==\n'''\"Conservative.bg\"''' platform publishes an annual edition called ''''\"YearBook\"'''. The first issue came out in 2018.\n[[File:\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044a-\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0448\u043d\u0438\u043a\u044a.png|thumb|'''YearBook 2019,''' published by the Conservative.bg platform]]\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.conservative.bg/ Official website]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/diasnaplatforma Facebook page]\n* [https://www.booktrading.bg/konservator-2019 YearBook]\n[[Category:Digital media]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044a|\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044a (\u043f\u043e\u044f\u0441\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435)}}{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = Conservative.bg\n| logo = \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044a-\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e.png\n| publisher = Conservative.bg LTD\n| depeditor = Mihail Krustev\n| political = conservative\n| language = Bulgarian\n| chiefeditor = Nikolay Oblakoff\n}}'''\"Conservative.bg'\"''' is a Bulgarian online platform for opinions, analyzes and comments with a right-wing conservative focus and emphasis on political, social and cultural topics.\n\nInitially, the platform was founded in 2017 under the name '''\"Misal\"''' (\"Thought\" in bulgarian) but after a merger with another media '''\"The Five Corners\"''' in 2018\u00a0 is renamed to the '''\"Conservative.bg\"'''.\n\n== Conservative.bg right-wing platform ==\nRight-wing platform '''\"Conservative.bg\"''' offers free access to all of its content, as well as to its annual review edition. The media was founded in 2017 in order to be an Internet portal for opinions and analyzes from a right conservative perspective.\n\nThe site founders are Nikolay Oblakoff, Mihail Krastev, Boyan Zlatanov, Emil Vulkov, Simeon Popov and Teodor Dimokenchev. All of them remain editors to this day. Popular columnists include Krystian Szkwarek, Dimitar Petrov, Toncho Kraevski, Ivan Stambolov - Sula, Toma Petrov, Dimitar Vuchev, Boris Stanimirov and Nikola Filipov.\n\nGuest authors on the platform are popular names in political, social and cultural life, such as Martin Tabakov, Petar Nikolov, Lyubomir Kanov, [[Angel Dzhambazki]], Kuzman Iliev , Toma Bikov, [[Andrey Novakov]], Vladimir Sirkarov, Alex Alexiev, Villy Lilkov and others.\n\nIn addition to the website and the annual review edition, '''\"Conservative.bg\"''' platform also organizes public discussions on social and political topics. Among the participants of these events are Ognian Minchev, Haralan Alexandrov, [[Ryszard Legutko]], Dimitar Stoyanovich, Boyan Rashev, Krasen Stanchev, [[Boyko Vasilev|Boyko Vasilev,]] Neno Dimov and others.\n\n== \u0412\u044a\u043d\u0448\u043d\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0438 ==\n'''\"Conservative.bg\"''' platform is the successor to the '''\"Misal\"''' platform, created through its merger with another online media '''\"The Five Corners\"'''. The platform uses the domain of the related to it Conservative Youth Club.\n\nThe first issue of '''\"YearBook\"''' is published in 2018.\n\nSince 10.07.2019 '''\"Conservative.bg\"''' is a registered trademark within the European Union with number 00106021.\n\n== Sections ==\n'''\"Politics\"''' - political analyzes from Bulgaria and the world\n\n'''\"Society\"''' - community and social topics\n\n'''\"Libertarian\"''' - economical and financial analysis\n\n'''\"Thought\"''' - views on culture and science\n\n'''\"On This Day\"''' - a historical overview\n\n== Editorial staff ==\n'''Editor-in-chief''' - Nikolay Oblakov\n\n'''Deputy editor''' - Mihail Krastev\n\n'''Editorial Board''' - Boyan Zlatanov, Teodor Dimokenchev, Nikola Bushnyakov, Emil Valkov, Simeon Popov, Leda Necheva, Ivo Georgiev, Toma Petrov\n\n'''Columnists''' - Nikola Filipov, Victoria Georgieva, Krystian Szkwarek, Toncho Kraevski, Dimitar Petrov, Svetoslav Alexandrov, Boris Stanimirov, Martin Tabakov, Lachezar Tomov, Stefan Stoyanov, Christian Anadoliev, Dimitar Vuchev, Ivan Stambolov - Sula, Vladislav Apostolov, Georgi Zayakov\n\n== YearBook ==\n'''\"Conservative.bg\"''' platform publishes an annual edition called ''''\"YearBook\"'''. The first issue came out in 2018.\n[[File:\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044a-\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0448\u043d\u0438\u043a\u044a.png|thumb|'''YearBook 2019,''' published by the Conservative.bg platform]]\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.conservative.bg/ Official website]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/diasnaplatforma Facebook page]\n* [https://www.booktrading.bg/konservator-2019 YearBook]\n[[Category:Digital media]]\n", "name_user": "Spindoc795", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conservative.bg"}
{"title_page": "Iron lung", "text_new": "{{short description|Mechanical respirator}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{lead too short|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox medical intervention\n|  Name        = Negative pressure ventilator\n|  Image       = Iron lung CDC.jpg\n|  Caption     = An Emerson iron lung. The patient lies within the chamber, which when sealed provides an effectively oscillating atmospheric pressure. This particular machine was donated to the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] Museum by the family of [[poliomyelitis]] patient Barton Hebert of Covington, Louisiana, who had used the device from the late 1950s until his death in 2003.\n|  ICD10       =\n|  ICD9        = {{ICD9proc|93.99}}\n|  MeshID      = D015919\n|  OPS301      =\n|  OtherCodes  =\n|  HCPCSlevel2 =\n}}\n\nA '''negative pressure ventilator''', also known as '''iron lung''' (colloquialism) or ''' pulmotor''' ([[generic trademark]]), is a [[medical ventilator|mechanical respirator]] which enables a person to [[breathing|breathe]] on his or her own in a normal manner, when [[Muscles of respiration|muscle]] control is lost, or the work of breathing exceeds the person's ability. \n\nAn \"iron lung\" is typically a large horizontal cylinder, in which a person is laid, with their head protruding from a hole in the end of the cylinder, so that their head (particularly nose and mouth) are outside the cylinder, exposed to ambient air, and the rest of their body sealed inside the cylinder, where air pressure is continuously cycled up and down (up to, or above -- and then below -- ambient room pressure), to stimulate breathing.<ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\">Rockoff, Mark, M.D., [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cUCqsl6JROg \"The Iron Lung and Polio,\"], video (8 minutes), January 11, 2016, OPENPediatrics and [[Boston Children's Hospital]] on [[YouTube]], retrieved April 11, 2020 (historical background and images, explanatory diagrams, and live demonstrations)</ref><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\">[https://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/objects-and-stories/medicine/iron-lung \"The Iron Lung,\"] [[Science Museum Group]], Kensington, [[London, England]], U.K. (moderately detailed, illustrated description of the device and its application -- and history), retrieved April 11, 2020</ref><ref name=\"how_does_iron_lung_work_2018_08_21_newsweek\">\n[https://www.newsweek.com/how-does-iron-lung-work-polio-survivor-last-us-1083104 \"How Does Iron Lung Work?: Polio Survivor, 82, Among Last to Use Breathing Equipment,\"] August 21, 2018, ''[[Newsweek]]'' retrieved April 11, 2020</ref>\n\nNeed for this treatment may result from certain diseases (e.g. [[polio]], [[botulism]]) and certain poisons (e.g. [[barbiturates]], [[tubocurarine]]).\n\nIts use is largely obsolete in modern medicine, as superior breathing therapies have been developed{{cn|date=March 2020}}, and due to the eradication of [[polio]] in most of the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=America's last iron lung users on their lives spent inside obsolete ventilators|work=[[The Independent]]|first=Andrew|last=Buncombe|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/polio-iron-lung-survivors-photos-lives-inside-ventilators-a8070881.html|date=2017-11-22}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in 2020, the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] revived some interest in the device as a cheap, readily-producible substitute for positive-ventilation [[Medical ventilator|ventilators]], which were feared to be outnumbered by potential victims temporarily needing artificially assisted respiration.<ref name=\"modern_iron_lung_2020_04_06_newatlas\">[https://newatlas.com/medical/british-engineers-modern-iron-lung-covid-19-ventilator-alternative/ \"Modern iron lung designed to address ventilator shortage,\"], April 06, 2020, ''[[New Atlas]],'' retrieved April 11, 2020 (note detailed reader comment, , April 7, 2020, by Christopher Smith, with clinical application details.)</ref><ref name=\"one_kansas_company_2020_04_09_ksn_com\">[https://www.ksn.com/news/one-kansas-company-is-switching-gears-to-make-iron-lung-ventilators/  \"One Kansas company is switching gears to make iron lung ventilators,\"] (video & text), April 10, 2020, ''[[KSNW-TV]],'' retrieved April 11, 2020</ref><ref name=\"hess_offers_2020_04_09_hdnews_net\">Allen, Margaret, [https://www.hdnews.net/news/20200409/hess-offers-iron-lung-for-covid-19 \"Hess offers iron lung for COVID-19,\"] April 9, 2020, ''[[Hays Daily News]],'' retrieved April 11, 2020</ref>\n\n==Design and function==\n\nThe device is typically a large horizontal cylinder, in which a person is laid, with their head protruding from a hole in the end of the cylinder, so that their head (particularly nose and mouth) are outside the cylinder, exposed to ambient air, and the rest of their body sealed inside the cylinder, where air pressure is continuously cycled up and down, to stimulate breathing.<ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" /><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\" /><ref name=\"how_does_iron_lung_work_2018_08_21_newsweek\" />\n\nTo cause the patient to inhale, air is pumped out of the cylinder, causing a slight vacuum, which causes the patient's chest and abdomen to expand (drawing air from outside the cylinder, through the patient's exposed nose or mouth, into their lungs). Then, for the patient to exhale, the air inside the cylinder is compressed slightly (or allowed to equalize to ambient room pressure), causing the patient's chest and abdomen to partially collapse, forcing air out of the lungs, as the patient exhales the breath through their exposed mouth and nose, outside the cylinder.<ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" /><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\" /><ref name=\"how_does_iron_lung_work_2018_08_21_newsweek\" />\n\nExamples of the device include the Drinker respirator, the Emerson respirator, and the Both (or Emerson\u2013Drinker) respirator. \n\n:NOTE: The negative form of pressure ventilation (decreasing surrounding pressure to induce inhalation then repressurizing to [[bar (unit)|{{convert|1|bar|psi mmHg}}]] has been almost entirely superseded by [[positive pressure ventilation]] (forcing air into the lungs with a pressure greater than 1 bar then allowing the body to naturally exhale before repeating) or negative pressure cuirass ventilation.\n\nIron lungs can be either manually or mechanically/electrically powered, but normally are powered by an electric motor linked to a flexible pumping diaphragm (commonly on opposite the end of the cylinder from the patient's head).<ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" />\n\nLarger \"room-sized\" iron lungs were also developed, allowing for simultaneous ventilation of several patients (each with their heads protruding from sealed openings in the outer wall), with sufficient space inside for a nurse to be inside the sealed room, attending the patients.<ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" />\n\nSmaller, single-patient versions of the iron lung include the so-called \"exovent\" or \"Cuirass ventilator\" (named for the Medieval-era [[Cuirass]], a torso-covering [[body armor]]).  The Cuirass ventilator encloses only the patient's torso, or chest and abdomen, but otherwise operates essentially the same as the original, full-sized iron lung.<ref name=\"modern_iron_lung_2020_04_06_newatlas\" /><ref name=\"iron_lung_and_2020_04_11_oxy_gen\">[http://oxygen.milano.it/en/the-iron-lung-and-the-modern-ventilation/ \"The 'iron lung' and the modern 'ventilation',\"] Oxy.gen, \nretrieved April 11, 2020 (caution: source unclear; apparently an Italian oxygen-supplier)</ref>\n\n==Method and use==\nHumans, like most mammals, breathe by ''negative pressure'' breathing:<ref name=stemnet>{{cite web|title=Gas Exchange in Humans|url=http://www.stemnet.nf.ca/~dpower/resp/exchange.htm|accessdate=2011-07-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423113840/http://www.stemnet.nf.ca/~dpower/resp/exchange.htm|archivedate=2009-04-23}}</ref> the rib cage expands and the [[Thoracic diaphragm|diaphragm]] contracts, expanding the [[chest cavity]]. This causes the pressure in the chest cavity to decrease, and the [[lung]]s expand to fill the space. This, in turn, causes the pressure of the air inside the lungs to decrease (it becomes negative, relative to the atmosphere), and air flows into the lungs from the atmosphere: [[inhalation]]. When the diaphragm relaxes, the reverse happens and the person [[exhalation|exhales]]. If a person loses part or all of the ability to control the muscles involved, breathing becomes difficult or impossible.\n\n==Invention and early use==\n[[File:Museum-gt-eiserne-lunge.jpg|thumb|Iron lung from the 1950s in the [[Stadtmuseum G\u00fctersloh|G\u00fctersloh Town Museum]]. In Germany, fewer than a dozen of these breathing machines are available to the public.]]\nIn 1670, English scientist [[John Mayow]] came up with the idea of external negative pressure ventilation. Mayow built a model consisting of bellows and a [[Waterskin|bladder]] to pull in and expel air.<ref name=Schlager2000>{{cite book|last=Schlager|first=Neil|title=Science and Its Times: Understanding the Social Significance of Scientific Discovery, Vol. 6: 1900-1950|page=[https://archive.org/details/scienceitstimesu0000unse/page/348 348]|publisher=Gale|location=Farmington Hills, Michigan|year=2000|isbn=978-0787639389|url=https://archive.org/details/scienceitstimesu0000unse/page/348}}</ref>\nThe first negative pressure ventilator was described by Scottish physician John Dalziel in 1832. Successful use of similar devices was described a few years later. Early prototypes included a hand-operated bellows-driven \"Spirophore\" designed by Dr Woillez of Paris (1876),<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Emerson |first1=John H |title=Some Reflections on Iron Lungs and Other Inventions |journal=Respiratory Care |date=July 1998 |volume=43| issue = 7 |page=577 |url=http://www.jhemerson.com/pdfs/Emerson%20-%20Some%20reflections%20%281998%29.pdf |accessdate=12 October 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060324195608/http://www.jhemerson.com/pdfs/Emerson%20-%20Some%20reflections%20%281998%29.pdf |archivedate=24 March 2006 }}</ref> and an airtight wooden box designed specifically for the treatment of polio by Dr Stueart of South Africa (1918). Stueart's box was sealed at the waist and shoulders with clay and powered by motor-driven bellows.<ref name=\"Gould\">{{cite book| last=Gould| first=Tony| title=A Summer Plague: Polio and Its Survivors| publisher=[[Yale University Press]]| location=New Haven| year=1997| page=90| isbn=978-0300072761}}</ref>\nThe first of these devices to be widely used however was developed in 1928 by Drinker and Shaw of the United States.<ref name=Gilgoff2002>{{cite book|editor-last=Gilgoff|editor-first=Irene S.|last=Laurie|first=Gini|title=Breath of Life: The Role of the Ventilator in Managing Life-Threatening Illnesses|chapter=Ventilator users, home care, and independent living: a historical perspective|pages=161\u2013201|publisher=Scarecrow Press, Inc.|location=Lanham, Maryland|year=2002|isbn=978-0-8108-3488-0|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ngA1izcCrFQC&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=%22Ventilator+users,+home+care,+and+independent+living:+a+historical+perspective%22#v=onepage&q=%22Ventilator%20users%2C%20home%20care%2C%20and%20independent%20living%3A%20a%20historical%20perspective%22&f=false}}</ref> The iron lung, often referred to in the early days as the \"Drinker respirator\", was invented by [[Philip Drinker]] (1894\u20131972) and [[Louis Agassiz Shaw, Jr.]], [[professor]]s of [[Occupational hygiene|industrial hygiene]] at the [[Harvard School of Public Health]].<ref name=Sherwood1973>{{cite journal|last1=Sherwood|first1=RJ|title=Obituaries: Philip Drinker 1894\u20131972|journal=The Annals of Occupational Hygiene|volume=16|issue=1|pages=93\u20134|year=1973|doi=10.1093/annhyg/16.1.93}}</ref><ref name=Gorham1979>{{cite journal|last1=Gorham|first1=J|title=A medical triumph: the iron lung|journal=Respiratory Therapy|volume=9|issue=1|pages=71\u20133|year=1979|pmc=|pmid=10297356|doi=|url=}}</ref><ref name=OSHHarvard>{{cite web|title=2010-2011 Student Handbook|publisher=The Harvard Education and Research Center for Occupational Safety and Health|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|year=2010|url=http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/research/erc/files/no_whoswho_editsept10updates.pdf |accessdate=2011-07-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110102095012/http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/research/erc/files/no_whoswho_editsept10updates.pdf|archive-date=2011-01-02}}</ref><ref name=Lehigh>{{cite web|author=P.C. Rossin College of Engineering and Applied Science|title=Philip Drinker '17|work=Distinguished Alumni: Great Talents & Bright Minds|publisher=Lehigh University|location=Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|year=2011|url=http://www3.lehigh.edu/engineering/about/drinker.asp|accessdate=2011-07-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615142114/http://www3.lehigh.edu/engineering/about/drinker.asp|archivedate=2011-06-15}}</ref> The machine was powered by an electric motor with air pumps from two vacuum cleaners. The air pumps changed the pressure inside a rectangular, airtight metal box, pulling air in and out of the lungs.<ref name=NMAH2011>{{cite web|author=Kenneth E. Behring Center|title=The iron lung and other equipment|work=Whatever happened to polio?|publisher=National Museum of American History|location=Washington, DC|year=2011|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/polio/howpolio/ironlung.htm|accessdate=2011-07-02}}</ref>\n\nThe first clinical use of the Drinker respirator on a human was on 12 October 1928, at the [[Boston Children's Hospital]] in the US.<ref name=Gorham1979/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tebyan.net/Events_History/World_Events/2010/10/12/140096.html |title=Today in History: Iron Lung Used for the First Time (1928) |publisher=Tebyan.net |date= |accessdate=2013-11-14}}</ref> The subject was an eight-year-old girl who was nearly dead as a result of [[respiratory failure]] due to [[poliomyelitis|polio]].<ref name=Lehigh/> Her dramatic recovery, within less than a minute of being placed in the chamber, helped popularize the new device.<ref name=OSHHarvard/>\n\nBoston manufacturer Warren E. Collins began production of the iron lung that year.<ref name=Silver2007>{{cite book|author1=Julie K. Silver|author2=Daniel J. Wilson|title=Polio Voices|location=Santa Barbara|publisher=Praeger Publishers|year=2007|page=141|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qOIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA975&dq=Popular+Science+1930+plane+%22Popular+Mechanics%22&hl=en&ei=_7BlTsWeBYTWgQf9mIiLCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&sqi=2&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q&f=true \"Artificial Lung on Wheels Prove Life Saver\" ''Popular Mechanics'', December 1930] photo of earliest production units from Boston</ref> Although it was initially developed for the treatment of victims of [[coal gas]] poisoning, it was most famously used in the mid-20th century for the treatment of respiratory failure caused by poliomyelitis.<ref name=Sherwood1973/>\n\nDanish physiologist [[August Krogh]], upon returning to Copenhagen in 1931 from a visit to New York where he saw the Drinker machine in use, constructed the first Danish respirator designed for clinical purposes. Krogh's device differed from Drinker's in that its motor was powered by water from the city pipelines. Krogh also made an infant respirator version.<ref name=\"Kirby\">{{cite book| last=Kirby| first=Richard R.| title=Mechanical Ventilation| publisher=[[Churchill Livingstone]]| location=New York| year=1985| page=9| isbn=978-0443080630}}</ref>\n\nIn 1931, [[John Haven Emerson]] (5 February 1906{{spaced ndash}}4 February 1997) introduced an improved and less expensive iron lung.<ref name=Geddes2007>{{cite journal|last=Geddes|first=LA|title=The history of artificial respiration|journal=IEEE Engineering in Medicine and Biology Magazine|volume=26|issue=6|pages=38\u201341|year=2007|pmid=18189086|doi=10.1109/EMB.2007.907081}}</ref><ref name=\"NMAH lung\">{{cite web|author=|title=Iron Lung|publisher=National Museum of American History|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/collections/object.cfm?key=35&objkey=114|accessdate=2011-07-01}}</ref> The Emerson iron lung had a bed that could slide in and out of the cylinder as needed, and the tank had portal windows which allowed attendants to reach in and adjust limbs, sheets, or hot packs.<ref name=NMAH2011/> Drinker and Harvard University sued Emerson, claiming he had infringed on patent rights. Emerson defended himself by making the case that such lifesaving devices should be freely available to all.<ref name=NMAH2011/> Emerson also demonstrated that every aspect of Drinker's patents had been published or used by others at earlier times. Since an invention must be novel to be patentable, prior publication/use of the invention meant it was not novel and therefore unpatentable. Emerson won the case, and Drinker's patents were declared invalid.\n\nThe United Kingdom's first iron lung was designed in 1934 by Robert Henderson, an Aberdeen doctor. Henderson had seen a demonstration of the Drinker respirator in the early 1930s, and built a device of his own upon his return to Scotland. Four weeks after its construction, the Henderson respirator was used to save the life of a 10-year-old boy from New Deer, Aberdeenshire, who was suffering from poliomyelitis. Despite this success, Henderson was reprimanded for secretly using hospital facilities to build the machine.<ref name=\"Wills\">{{cite book| last=Wills| first=Elspeth| title=Scottish Firsts: A Celebration of Innovation and Achievement| publisher=[[Mainstream Publishing]]| location=Edinburgh| year=2002| pages=[https://archive.org/details/scottishfirstsce00will/page/51 51\u20132]| isbn=978-1840186116| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/scottishfirstsce00will/page/51}}</ref><ref name=\"Thomas\">{{cite web| last=Thomas| first=Campbell| date=15 February 2000| url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/dr-robert-henderson-1.249085| title=Dr Robert Henderson | work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]| accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Both respirator==\n[[File:Both Cabinet Respirator in WWII.jpg|thumb|right|250px|A Both cabinet respirator being used to treat a patient at the 110th Australian Military Hospital in 1943]]\n{{main|Both respirator}}\nThe [[Both respirator]], a negative pressure ventilator, was invented in 1937 when Australia's epidemic of poliomyelitis created an immediate need for more ventilating machines to compensate for respiratory paralysis. Although the Drinker model was effective and saved lives, its widespread use was hindered by the fact that the machines were very large, heavy (about 750 lbs), bulky, and expensive. In the US, an adult machine cost about $2000 in 1930, and \u00a32000 delivered to Melbourne in 1936. The cost in Europe in the mid-1950s was around \u00a31500. Consequently, there were few of the Drinker devices in Australia and Europe.<ref name=\"Trubuhovich\">{{cite journal |last=Trubuhovich| first=Ronald V.| title=Notable Australian contributions to the management of ventilatory failure of acute poliomyelitis| journal=Critical Care and Resuscitation| year=2006| volume=8| issue=4| pages=383\u20135| pmid=17227281}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Government of South Australia#Department for Health and Ageing (SA Health)|South Australia Health Department]] asked Adelaide brothers Edward and Don Both to create an inexpensive \"iron lung\".<ref name=\"Healey\">{{cite web| last=Healey| first=John| year=1998| url=http://www.samhs.org.au/Virtual%20Museum/Medicine/Bothurinlung/bothironlung-netley.html| title=The Both Brothers and the 'Iron Lung' | publisher=South Australian Medical Heritage Society Inc| accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> Biomedical engineer [[Edward Both]] designed and developed a cabinet respirator made of plywood that worked similarly to the Drinker device, with the addition of a bi-valved design which allowed temporary access to the patient's body.<ref name=\"Trubuhovich\" /> Far cheaper to make (only \u00a3100) than the Drinker machine, the Both Respirator also weighed less and could be constructed and transported more quickly.<ref name=\"Trubuhovich\" /><ref name=\"SMH\">{{cite news| date=2004-12-07| url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/National/Memories-of-polio-and-those-who-wrestled-with-it/2004/12/06/1102182223039.html| title=Memories of polio and those who wrestled with it | newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]| accessdate=2013-03-10}}</ref> Such was the demand for the machines that they were often used by patients within an hour of production.<ref name=\"Langmore\">{{cite book| editor-last=Langmore| editor-first=Diane| title=Australian Dictionary of Biography: Volume 17 1981-1990 A-K| publisher=[[Melbourne University Publishing]]| location=Carlton, Victoria| year=2009| page=129| isbn=978-0522853827}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Morris Iron Lung Thackray.jpg|thumb|right|Both-Nuffield iron lung display at the [[Thackray Medical Museum]], Leeds. Pictures show assembly at the Morris motor works]]\nVisiting London in 1938 during another polio epidemic, Both produced additional respirators there which attracted the attention of [[William Morris, 1st Viscount Nuffield|William Morris]] (Lord Nuffield), a British motor manufacturer and philanthropist. Nuffield, intrigued by the design, financed the production of approximately 1700 machines at his [[Morris Motors|car factory]] in [[Cowley, Oxfordshire|Cowley]], and donated them to hospitals throughout all parts of Britain and the British Empire.<ref name=\"Langmore\" /> Soon, the Both-Nuffield respirators were able to be produced by the thousand at about one-thirteenth the cost of the American design.<ref name=\"Healey\" /> By the early 1950s, there were over 700 Both-Nuffield iron lungs in the United Kingdom, but only 50 Drinker devices.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lawrence|first=Ghislaine|title=The Smith-Clarke Respirator|journal=[[The Lancet]]|date=2002-02-23|volume=359|pmid=11879908|issue=9307|page=716|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(02)07819-4}}</ref>\n\n==Modern usage==\n[[Image:Poumon artificiel.jpg|thumb|Staff in a [[Rhode Island]] hospital are examining a patient in an iron lung tank respirator during a polio epidemic in Rhode Island in 1960. The iron lung encased the [[thoracic cavity]] in an air-tight chamber used to create a negative pressure around the thoracic cavity, thereby causing air to enter the lungs to equalize [[Breathing#Mechanics|intrapulmonary pressure]] ]]\nRows of iron lungs filled hospital wards at the height of the polio outbreaks of the 1940s and 1950s, helping children, and some adults, with bulbar polio and bulbospinal polio. A polio patient with a paralyzed diaphragm would typically spend two weeks inside an iron lung while recovering.<ref name=\"NMAH\">{{Cite web| url=http://amhistory.si.edu/polio/howpolio/ironlung.htm| title=NMAH &#124; Polio: The Iron Lung and Other Equipment| website=[[National Museum of American History]]| publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]]| accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2012/01/what-america-looked-like-polio-children-paralyzed-in-iron-lungs/251098/|title=What America Looked Like: Polio Children Paralyzed in Iron Lungs|first=Brian|last=Resnick|date=January 10, 2012|website=The Atlantic}}</ref>\n\n[[Polio vaccine|Polio vaccination]] programs have virtually [[Poliomyelitis eradication|eradicated]] new cases of poliomyelitis in the developed world. Because of this, and the development of modern [[Medical ventilator|ventilators]], and widespread use of [[tracheal intubation]] and [[tracheotomy]], the iron lung has mostly disappeared from modern medicine. In 1959, there were 1,200 people using tank respirators in the United States, but by 2004 there were only 39.<ref name=\"NMAH\" /> By 2014, there were only 10 people left with an iron lung.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/aug/24/north-texan-one-of-10-still-living-in-iron-lung/| title=North Texan one of 10 still living in iron lung| first=Shelly| last=Conlon| date=24 August 2014| agency=Associated Press| publisher=The Washington Times| accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Positive pressure ventilation]] systems are now more common than negative pressure systems. Positive pressure ventilators work by blowing air into the patient's lungs via [[intubation]] through the airway; they were used for the first time in [[Blegdams Hospital]], [[Copenhagen]], Denmark, during a polio outbreak in 1952.<ref name=Reisner2009>{{cite web|author=Louise Reisner-S\u00e9n\u00e9lar|title=The Danish anaesthesiologist Bj\u00f6rn Ibsen a pioneer of long-term ventilation on the upper airways|year=2009|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B7CdB217pf6yN2QxOGI5NTUtZWIzYS00N2NhLWFhODQtOGZjMjdhZTlkZGE5&hl=de|accessdate=2011-07-01}}</ref><ref name=Wackers1994>{{cite book|last=Wackers|first=Ger|chapter=Chapter 4: |title=Theaters of truth and competence. Intermittent positive pressure respiration during the 1952 polio-epidemic in Copenhagen|year=1994|chapter-url=http://www.fdcw.unimaas.nl/personal/WebSitesMWT/Wackers/proefschrift.html#h4|accessdate=2011-07-01|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223223131/http://www.fdcw.unimaas.nl/personal/WebSitesMWT/Wackers/proefschrift.html#h4|archivedate=2007-12-23}}</ref> It proved a success and soon superseded the iron lung throughout Europe.\n\nThe iron lung now has a marginal place in modern [[respiratory therapy]]. Most patients with paralysis of the breathing muscles use modern [[mechanical ventilation|mechanical ventilators]] that push air into the airway with positive pressure. These are generally efficacious and have the advantage of not restricting patients' movements or caregivers' ability to examine the patients as significantly as an iron lung does. However, [[wikt:negative pressure|negative pressure]] ventilation is a truer approximation of normal physiological breathing and results in more normal distribution of air in the lungs. It may also be preferable in certain rare conditions, such as [[central hypoventilation syndrome]], in which failure of the medullary respiratory centers at the base of the brain results in patients having no [[Autonomic nervous system|autonomic control]] of breathing. At least one reported polio patient, [[Dianne Odell]], had a spinal deformity that caused the use of mechanical ventilators to be [[contraindicated]].<ref name=Sydney2008>{{cite news|author=|title=Power failure kills iron lung lady|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=2008-05-29|url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/world/power-failure-kills-iron-lung-lady/2008/05/29/1211654160059.html|accessdate=2011-07-01}}</ref> There are patients who today still use the older machines, often in their homes, despite the occasional difficulty of finding the various replacement parts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/60-years-iron-lung-us-polio-survivor-worries-about-new-2D11641456|title=60 years in an iron lung: US polio survivor worries about new global threat|publisher=}}</ref> Joan Headley of [[Post-Polio Health International]] said that as of May 28, 2008, there were about 30 patients in the U.S. still using an iron lung.<ref name=CNN2008>{{cite news|title=Woman dies after life spent in iron lung |date=May 28, 2008 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/05/28/iron.lung.death.ap/index.html |accessdate=2011-07-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022162511/http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/05/28/iron.lung.death.ap/index.html |archivedate=October 22, 2008 }}</ref> That figure may be inaccurately low; [[Houston, Texas|Houston]] alone had 19 iron lung patients living at home in 2008.<ref name=Neergaard2009>{{cite news|author=Lauran Neergaard|title=Emergency officials struggle to find those on life-support during power outages|date=2009-01-13|url=http://www.ems1.com/survivability/articles/447100-Emergency-officials-struggle-to-find-those-on-life-support-during-power-outages|accessdate=2014-01-01}}</ref> [[Martha Mason (writer)|Martha Mason]] of [[Lattimore, North Carolina]], died on May 4, 2009, after spending 60 of her 72 years in an iron lung.<ref name=Fox2009>{{cite news|last=Fox|first=Margalit|title=Martha Mason, Who Wrote Book About Her Decades in an Iron Lung, Dies at 71|work=The New York Times|date=2009-05-10|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/10/us/10mason.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=iron%20lung&st=cse|accessdate=2011-07-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October 2009, [[June Middleton]] of [[Melbourne, Australia]], who had been entered in the ''[[Guinness Book of Records]]'' as the person who spent the longest time in an iron lung, died aged 83, having spent more than 60 years in her iron lung.<ref name=Sydney2009>{{cite news|author=|title=Dead after 60 years in iron lung|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=2009-11-01|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/dead-after-60-years-in-iron-lung-20091101-hqyy.html?autostart=1|accessdate=2011-07-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the [[Post-Polio Health International]] (PHI) organizations estimated that there were only six to eight iron lung users in the United States; as of 2017 its executive director knew of none. Press reports then emerged, however, of at least three (perhaps the last three)<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=MAZZIOTTA |first1=JULIE |title=Polio Survivor, 82, Is One of the Last 3 People in the U.S. to Use an Iron Lung |url=https://people.com/health/polio-survivor-last-3-people-use-iron-lung/ |magazine=People Magazine |date=August 21, 2018}}</ref> users of such devices,<ref name=\"The Last of the Iron Lungs\">{{Cite web |url=https://gizmodo.com/the-last-of-the-iron-lungs-1819079169 |title=The Last of the Iron Lungs |last=Brown |first=Jennings |date=2017-11-20 |website=Gizmodo |accessdate=2017-11-25}}</ref> sparking interest amongst those in the [[makerspace]] community such as [[Naomi Wu]]<ref name=\"Parts for an Iron Lung\">{{Cite web |url=https://hackaday.com/2017/11/25/a-callout-parts-for-an-iron-lung/ |title=A Callout: Parts for an Iron Lung |last=Lewin |first=Day |date=2017-11-25 |website=Hackaday |accessdate=2017-11-25}}</ref> in the manufacture of the obsolete components, particularly the gaskets.<ref name=\"Running out of collars for her iron lung.\">{{Cite tweet |number=933619850806620167 |user=reaksexycyborg |title=Via @NireBryce- we've got a nice old lady running out of collars for her iron lung. Lot of \ud83d\udca9 going on in the world we can't do anything about- but this seems 100% doable. @hackaday, @make, textile tech folks- any ideas? From https://gizmodo.com/the-last-of-the-iron-lungs-1819079169 \u2026 |author=Naomi Wu |date=2017-11-23}}</ref> Another is retired lawyer Paul Alexander, 72, of Dallas.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/world/americas/104416976/living-inside-a-canister-this-polio-survivor-is-one-of-few-people-left-using-iron-lung |title=Living inside a canister: this polio survivor is one of few people left using iron lung |publisher=Stuff (Fairfax) |date= 1 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2020, reacting to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], to address the urgent global shortage of modern [[Medical ventilator|ventilators]] (needed for patients with advanced, severe [[COVID-19]] disease), some enterprises developed prototypes of new, readily-producible versions of the iron lung. These developments included:\n* a compact, torso-sized \"exovent\" developed by a team in the [[United Kingdom]], which included the [[University of Warwick]], the [[Royal National Throat Nose and Ear Hospital]], the [[Marshall Aerospace and Defence Group]], the [[Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust]], along with teams of medical clinicians, academics, manufacturers, engineers and citizen scientists;<ref name=\"modern_iron_lung_2020_04_06_newatlas\" /> \n* a full-size iron lung developed in the [[United States]] by a team led by Hays Services, Inc., of [[Hays, Kansas]].<ref name=\"one_kansas_company_2020_04_09_ksn_com\" /><ref name=\"hess_offers_2020_04_09_hdnews_net\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last1=Emerson|first1=JH|authorlink1=John Haven Emerson|last2=Loynes|first2=JA|title=The evolution of iron lungs: respirators of the body-encasing type|publisher=J.H. Emerson Company|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|year=1978}}\n* [[Martha Mason (writer)|Martha Mason]], a polio survivor, penned a best-selling memoir, ''Breath'', about her life inside an iron lung.\n* [[Margaret Atwood]] mentions an iron lung in her book ''Cat's Eye''\n* [[Peg Kehret]] mentions the use of an iron lung in her autobiographical book, ''[[Small Steps: The Year I Got Polio]]''\n* [[Elizabeth Berg (author)|Elizabeth Berg]] shares a fictionalization of the true story of Pat Raming, the first woman to give birth to baby while in an iron lung, in her book, We are all Welcome Here. 2006.\n* [http://ariwatch.com/VS/TheIronLung/RespirationWithoutBreathing.htm Respiration Without Breathing] - about the Thunberg \"barospirator\" built by John Emerson.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Iron lungs}}\n* [http://historical.hsl.virginia.edu/ironlung/ \"Iron Lung.\"] Claude Moore Health Sciences Library, [[University of Virginia]]\n* [http://www.powerhousemuseum.com/australia_innovates/?Section_id=1030&article_id=10022&behaviour=view_article Both respirator] at the [[Powerhouse Museum]]\n\n{{Respiratory system procedures}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|History}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iron Lung}}\n[[Category:Medical pumps]]\n[[Category:Polio]]\n[[Category:Respiratory therapy]]\n[[Category:1928 introductions]]\n[[Category:Mechanical ventilation]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mechanical respirator}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{lead too short|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox medical intervention\n|  Name        = Negative pressure ventilator\n|  Image       = Iron lung CDC.jpg\n|  Caption     = An Emerson iron lung. The patient lies within the chamber, which when sealed provides an effectively oscillating atmospheric pressure. This particular machine was donated to the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] Museum by the family of [[poliomyelitis]] patient Barton Hebert of Covington, Louisiana, who had used the device from the late 1950s until his death in 2003.\n|  ICD10       =\n|  ICD9        = {{ICD9proc|93.99}}\n|  MeshID      = D015919\n|  OPS301      =\n|  OtherCodes  =\n|  HCPCSlevel2 =\n}}\n\nA '''negative pressure ventilator''', also known as '''iron lung''' (colloquialism) or ''' pulmotor''' ([[generic trademark]]), is a [[medical ventilator|mechanical respirator]] which enables a person to [[breathing|breathe]] on his or her own in a normal manner, when [[Muscles of respiration|muscle]] control is lost, or the work of breathing exceeds the person's ability. \n\nAn \"iron lung\" is typically a large horizontal cylinder, in which a person is laid, with their head protruding from a hole in the end of the cylinder, so that their head (particularly nose and mouth) are outside the cylinder, exposed to ambient air, and the rest of their body sealed inside the cylinder, where air pressure is continuously cycled up and down (up to, or above -- and then below -- ambient room pressure), to stimulate breathing.<ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\">Rockoff, Mark, M.D., [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cUCqsl6JROg \"The Iron Lung and Polio,\"], video (8 minutes), January 11, 2016, OPENPediatrics and [[Boston Children's Hospital]] on [[YouTube]], retrieved April 11, 2020 (historical background and images, explanatory diagrams, and live demonstrations)</ref><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\">[https://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/objects-and-stories/medicine/iron-lung \"The Iron Lung,\"] [[Science Museum Group]], Kensington, [[London, England]], U.K. (moderately detailed, illustrated description of the device and its application -- and history), retrieved April 11, 2020</ref><ref name=\"how_does_iron_lung_work_2018_08_21_newsweek\">\n[https://www.newsweek.com/how-does-iron-lung-work-polio-survivor-last-us-1083104 \"How Does Iron Lung Work?: Polio Survivor, 82, Among Last to Use Breathing Equipment,\"] August 21, 2018, ''[[Newsweek]]'' retrieved April 11, 2020</ref>\n\nNeed for this treatment may result from certain diseases (e.g. [[polio]], [[botulism]]) and certain poisons (e.g. [[barbiturates]], [[tubocurarine]]).\n\nIts use is largely obsolete in modern medicine, as superior breathing therapies have been developed{{cn|date=March 2020}}, and due to the eradication of [[polio]] in most of the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=America's last iron lung users on their lives spent inside obsolete ventilators|work=[[The Independent]]|first=Andrew|last=Buncombe|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/polio-iron-lung-survivors-photos-lives-inside-ventilators-a8070881.html|date=2017-11-22}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in 2020, the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] revived some interest in the device as a cheap, readily-producible substitute for positive-ventilation [[medical ventilators|ventilators]], which were feared to be outnumbered by potential victims temporarily needing artificially assisted respiration.<ref name=\"modern_iron_lung_2020_04_06_newatlas\">[https://newatlas.com/medical/british-engineers-modern-iron-lung-covid-19-ventilator-alternative/ \"Modern iron lung designed to address ventilator shortage,\"], April 06, 2020, ''[[New Atlas]],'' retrieved April 11, 2020 (note detailed reader comment, , April 7, 2020, by Christopher Smith, with clinical application details.)</ref><ref name=\"one_kansas_company_2020_04_09_ksn_com\">[https://www.ksn.com/news/one-kansas-company-is-switching-gears-to-make-iron-lung-ventilators/  \"One Kansas company is switching gears to make iron lung ventilators,\"] (video & text), April 10, 2020, ''[[KSNW-TV]],'' retrieved April 11, 2020</ref><ref name=\"hess_offers_2020_04_09_hdnews_net\">Allen, Margaret, [https://www.hdnews.net/news/20200409/hess-offers-iron-lung-for-covid-19 \"Hess offers iron lung for COVID-19,\"] April 9, 2020, ''[[Hays Daily News]],'' retrieved April 11, 2020</ref>\n\n==Design and function==\n\nThe device is typically a large horizontal cylinder, in which a person is laid, with their head protruding from a hole in the end of the cylinder, so that their head (particularly nose and mouth) are outside the cylinder, exposed to ambient air, and the rest of their body sealed inside the cylinder, where air pressure is continuously cycled up and down, to stimulate breathing.<ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" /><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\" /><ref name=\"how_does_iron_lung_work_2018_08_21_newsweek\" />\n\nTo cause the patient to inhale, air is pumped out of the cylinder, causing a slight vacuum, which causes the patient's chest and abdomen to expand (drawing air from outside the cylinder, through the patient's exposed nose or mouth, into their lungs). Then, for the patient to exhale, the air inside the cylinder is compressed slightly (or allowed to equalize to ambient room pressure), causing the patient's chest and abdomen to partially collapse, forcing air out of the lungs, as the patient exhales the breath through their exposed mouth and nose, outside the cylinder.<ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" /><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\" /><ref name=\"how_does_iron_lung_work_2018_08_21_newsweek\" />\n\nExamples of the device include the Drinker respirator, the Emerson respirator, and the Both (or Emerson\u2013Drinker) respirator. \n\n:NOTE: The negative form of pressure ventilation (decreasing surrounding pressure to induce inhalation then repressurizing to [[bar (unit)|{{convert|1|bar|psi mmHg}}]] has been almost entirely superseded by [[positive pressure ventilation]] (forcing air into the lungs with a pressure greater than 1 bar then allowing the body to naturally exhale before repeating) or negative pressure cuirass ventilation.\n\nIron lungs can be either manually or mechanically/electrically powered, but normally are powered by an electric motor linked to a flexible pumping diaphragm (commonly on opposite the end of the cylinder from the patient's head).<ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" />\n\nLarger \"room-sized\" iron lungs were also developed, allowing for simultaneous ventilation of several patients (each with their heads protruding from sealed openings in the outer wall), with sufficient space inside for a nurse to be inside the sealed room, attending the patients.<ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" />\n\nSmaller, single-patient versions of the iron lung include the so-called \"exovent\" or \"Cuirass ventilator\" (named for the Medieval-era [[Cuirass]], a torso-covering [[body armor]]).  The Cuirass ventilator encloses only the patient's torso, or chest and abdomen, but otherwise operates essentially the same as the original, full-sized iron lung.<ref name=\"modern_iron_lung_2020_04_06_newatlas\" /><ref name=\"iron_lung_and_2020_04_11_oxy_gen\">[http://oxygen.milano.it/en/the-iron-lung-and-the-modern-ventilation/ \"The 'iron lung' and the modern 'ventilation',\"] Oxy.gen, \nretrieved April 11, 2020 (caution: source unclear; apparently an Italian oxygen-supplier)</ref>\n\n==Method and use==\nHumans, like most mammals, breathe by ''negative pressure'' breathing:<ref name=stemnet>{{cite web|title=Gas Exchange in Humans|url=http://www.stemnet.nf.ca/~dpower/resp/exchange.htm|accessdate=2011-07-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423113840/http://www.stemnet.nf.ca/~dpower/resp/exchange.htm|archivedate=2009-04-23}}</ref> the rib cage expands and the [[Thoracic diaphragm|diaphragm]] contracts, expanding the [[chest cavity]]. This causes the pressure in the chest cavity to decrease, and the [[lung]]s expand to fill the space. This, in turn, causes the pressure of the air inside the lungs to decrease (it becomes negative, relative to the atmosphere), and air flows into the lungs from the atmosphere: [[inhalation]]. When the diaphragm relaxes, the reverse happens and the person [[exhalation|exhales]]. If a person loses part or all of the ability to control the muscles involved, breathing becomes difficult or impossible.\n\n==Invention and early use==\n[[File:Museum-gt-eiserne-lunge.jpg|thumb|Iron lung from the 1950s in the [[Stadtmuseum G\u00fctersloh|G\u00fctersloh Town Museum]]. In Germany, fewer than a dozen of these breathing machines are available to the public.]]\nIn 1670, English scientist [[John Mayow]] came up with the idea of external negative pressure ventilation. Mayow built a model consisting of bellows and a [[Waterskin|bladder]] to pull in and expel air.<ref name=Schlager2000>{{cite book|last=Schlager|first=Neil|title=Science and Its Times: Understanding the Social Significance of Scientific Discovery, Vol. 6: 1900-1950|page=[https://archive.org/details/scienceitstimesu0000unse/page/348 348]|publisher=Gale|location=Farmington Hills, Michigan|year=2000|isbn=978-0787639389|url=https://archive.org/details/scienceitstimesu0000unse/page/348}}</ref>\nThe first negative pressure ventilator was described by Scottish physician John Dalziel in 1832. Successful use of similar devices was described a few years later. Early prototypes included a hand-operated bellows-driven \"Spirophore\" designed by Dr Woillez of Paris (1876),<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Emerson |first1=John H |title=Some Reflections on Iron Lungs and Other Inventions |journal=Respiratory Care |date=July 1998 |volume=43| issue = 7 |page=577 |url=http://www.jhemerson.com/pdfs/Emerson%20-%20Some%20reflections%20%281998%29.pdf |accessdate=12 October 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060324195608/http://www.jhemerson.com/pdfs/Emerson%20-%20Some%20reflections%20%281998%29.pdf |archivedate=24 March 2006 }}</ref> and an airtight wooden box designed specifically for the treatment of polio by Dr Stueart of South Africa (1918). Stueart's box was sealed at the waist and shoulders with clay and powered by motor-driven bellows.<ref name=\"Gould\">{{cite book| last=Gould| first=Tony| title=A Summer Plague: Polio and Its Survivors| publisher=[[Yale University Press]]| location=New Haven| year=1997| page=90| isbn=978-0300072761}}</ref>\nThe first of these devices to be widely used however was developed in 1928 by Drinker and Shaw of the United States.<ref name=Gilgoff2002>{{cite book|editor-last=Gilgoff|editor-first=Irene S.|last=Laurie|first=Gini|title=Breath of Life: The Role of the Ventilator in Managing Life-Threatening Illnesses|chapter=Ventilator users, home care, and independent living: a historical perspective|pages=161\u2013201|publisher=Scarecrow Press, Inc.|location=Lanham, Maryland|year=2002|isbn=978-0-8108-3488-0|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ngA1izcCrFQC&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=%22Ventilator+users,+home+care,+and+independent+living:+a+historical+perspective%22#v=onepage&q=%22Ventilator%20users%2C%20home%20care%2C%20and%20independent%20living%3A%20a%20historical%20perspective%22&f=false}}</ref> The iron lung, often referred to in the early days as the \"Drinker respirator\", was invented by [[Philip Drinker]] (1894\u20131972) and [[Louis Agassiz Shaw, Jr.]], [[professor]]s of [[Occupational hygiene|industrial hygiene]] at the [[Harvard School of Public Health]].<ref name=Sherwood1973>{{cite journal|last1=Sherwood|first1=RJ|title=Obituaries: Philip Drinker 1894\u20131972|journal=The Annals of Occupational Hygiene|volume=16|issue=1|pages=93\u20134|year=1973|doi=10.1093/annhyg/16.1.93}}</ref><ref name=Gorham1979>{{cite journal|last1=Gorham|first1=J|title=A medical triumph: the iron lung|journal=Respiratory Therapy|volume=9|issue=1|pages=71\u20133|year=1979|pmc=|pmid=10297356|doi=|url=}}</ref><ref name=OSHHarvard>{{cite web|title=2010-2011 Student Handbook|publisher=The Harvard Education and Research Center for Occupational Safety and Health|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|year=2010|url=http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/research/erc/files/no_whoswho_editsept10updates.pdf |accessdate=2011-07-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110102095012/http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/research/erc/files/no_whoswho_editsept10updates.pdf|archive-date=2011-01-02}}</ref><ref name=Lehigh>{{cite web|author=P.C. Rossin College of Engineering and Applied Science|title=Philip Drinker '17|work=Distinguished Alumni: Great Talents & Bright Minds|publisher=Lehigh University|location=Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|year=2011|url=http://www3.lehigh.edu/engineering/about/drinker.asp|accessdate=2011-07-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615142114/http://www3.lehigh.edu/engineering/about/drinker.asp|archivedate=2011-06-15}}</ref> The machine was powered by an electric motor with air pumps from two vacuum cleaners. The air pumps changed the pressure inside a rectangular, airtight metal box, pulling air in and out of the lungs.<ref name=NMAH2011>{{cite web|author=Kenneth E. Behring Center|title=The iron lung and other equipment|work=Whatever happened to polio?|publisher=National Museum of American History|location=Washington, DC|year=2011|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/polio/howpolio/ironlung.htm|accessdate=2011-07-02}}</ref>\n\nThe first clinical use of the Drinker respirator on a human was on 12 October 1928, at the [[Boston Children's Hospital]] in the US.<ref name=Gorham1979/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tebyan.net/Events_History/World_Events/2010/10/12/140096.html |title=Today in History: Iron Lung Used for the First Time (1928) |publisher=Tebyan.net |date= |accessdate=2013-11-14}}</ref> The subject was an eight-year-old girl who was nearly dead as a result of [[respiratory failure]] due to [[poliomyelitis|polio]].<ref name=Lehigh/> Her dramatic recovery, within less than a minute of being placed in the chamber, helped popularize the new device.<ref name=OSHHarvard/>\n\nBoston manufacturer Warren E. Collins began production of the iron lung that year.<ref name=Silver2007>{{cite book|author1=Julie K. Silver|author2=Daniel J. Wilson|title=Polio Voices|location=Santa Barbara|publisher=Praeger Publishers|year=2007|page=141|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qOIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA975&dq=Popular+Science+1930+plane+%22Popular+Mechanics%22&hl=en&ei=_7BlTsWeBYTWgQf9mIiLCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&sqi=2&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q&f=true \"Artificial Lung on Wheels Prove Life Saver\" ''Popular Mechanics'', December 1930] photo of earliest production units from Boston</ref> Although it was initially developed for the treatment of victims of [[coal gas]] poisoning, it was most famously used in the mid-20th century for the treatment of respiratory failure caused by poliomyelitis.<ref name=Sherwood1973/>\n\nDanish physiologist [[August Krogh]], upon returning to Copenhagen in 1931 from a visit to New York where he saw the Drinker machine in use, constructed the first Danish respirator designed for clinical purposes. Krogh's device differed from Drinker's in that its motor was powered by water from the city pipelines. Krogh also made an infant respirator version.<ref name=\"Kirby\">{{cite book| last=Kirby| first=Richard R.| title=Mechanical Ventilation| publisher=[[Churchill Livingstone]]| location=New York| year=1985| page=9| isbn=978-0443080630}}</ref>\n\nIn 1931, [[John Haven Emerson]] (5 February 1906{{spaced ndash}}4 February 1997) introduced an improved and less expensive iron lung.<ref name=Geddes2007>{{cite journal|last=Geddes|first=LA|title=The history of artificial respiration|journal=IEEE Engineering in Medicine and Biology Magazine|volume=26|issue=6|pages=38\u201341|year=2007|pmid=18189086|doi=10.1109/EMB.2007.907081}}</ref><ref name=\"NMAH lung\">{{cite web|author=|title=Iron Lung|publisher=National Museum of American History|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/collections/object.cfm?key=35&objkey=114|accessdate=2011-07-01}}</ref> The Emerson iron lung had a bed that could slide in and out of the cylinder as needed, and the tank had portal windows which allowed attendants to reach in and adjust limbs, sheets, or hot packs.<ref name=NMAH2011/> Drinker and Harvard University sued Emerson, claiming he had infringed on patent rights. Emerson defended himself by making the case that such lifesaving devices should be freely available to all.<ref name=NMAH2011/> Emerson also demonstrated that every aspect of Drinker's patents had been published or used by others at earlier times. Since an invention must be novel to be patentable, prior publication/use of the invention meant it was not novel and therefore unpatentable. Emerson won the case, and Drinker's patents were declared invalid.\n\nThe United Kingdom's first iron lung was designed in 1934 by Robert Henderson, an Aberdeen doctor. Henderson had seen a demonstration of the Drinker respirator in the early 1930s, and built a device of his own upon his return to Scotland. Four weeks after its construction, the Henderson respirator was used to save the life of a 10-year-old boy from New Deer, Aberdeenshire, who was suffering from poliomyelitis. Despite this success, Henderson was reprimanded for secretly using hospital facilities to build the machine.<ref name=\"Wills\">{{cite book| last=Wills| first=Elspeth| title=Scottish Firsts: A Celebration of Innovation and Achievement| publisher=[[Mainstream Publishing]]| location=Edinburgh| year=2002| pages=[https://archive.org/details/scottishfirstsce00will/page/51 51\u20132]| isbn=978-1840186116| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/scottishfirstsce00will/page/51}}</ref><ref name=\"Thomas\">{{cite web| last=Thomas| first=Campbell| date=15 February 2000| url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/dr-robert-henderson-1.249085| title=Dr Robert Henderson | work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]| accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Both respirator==\n[[File:Both Cabinet Respirator in WWII.jpg|thumb|right|250px|A Both cabinet respirator being used to treat a patient at the 110th Australian Military Hospital in 1943]]\n{{main|Both respirator}}\nThe [[Both respirator]], a negative pressure ventilator, was invented in 1937 when Australia's epidemic of poliomyelitis created an immediate need for more ventilating machines to compensate for respiratory paralysis. Although the Drinker model was effective and saved lives, its widespread use was hindered by the fact that the machines were very large, heavy (about 750 lbs), bulky, and expensive. In the US, an adult machine cost about $2000 in 1930, and \u00a32000 delivered to Melbourne in 1936. The cost in Europe in the mid-1950s was around \u00a31500. Consequently, there were few of the Drinker devices in Australia and Europe.<ref name=\"Trubuhovich\">{{cite journal |last=Trubuhovich| first=Ronald V.| title=Notable Australian contributions to the management of ventilatory failure of acute poliomyelitis| journal=Critical Care and Resuscitation| year=2006| volume=8| issue=4| pages=383\u20135| pmid=17227281}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Government of South Australia#Department for Health and Ageing (SA Health)|South Australia Health Department]] asked Adelaide brothers Edward and Don Both to create an inexpensive \"iron lung\".<ref name=\"Healey\">{{cite web| last=Healey| first=John| year=1998| url=http://www.samhs.org.au/Virtual%20Museum/Medicine/Bothurinlung/bothironlung-netley.html| title=The Both Brothers and the 'Iron Lung' | publisher=South Australian Medical Heritage Society Inc| accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> Biomedical engineer [[Edward Both]] designed and developed a cabinet respirator made of plywood that worked similarly to the Drinker device, with the addition of a bi-valved design which allowed temporary access to the patient's body.<ref name=\"Trubuhovich\" /> Far cheaper to make (only \u00a3100) than the Drinker machine, the Both Respirator also weighed less and could be constructed and transported more quickly.<ref name=\"Trubuhovich\" /><ref name=\"SMH\">{{cite news| date=2004-12-07| url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/National/Memories-of-polio-and-those-who-wrestled-with-it/2004/12/06/1102182223039.html| title=Memories of polio and those who wrestled with it | newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]| accessdate=2013-03-10}}</ref> Such was the demand for the machines that they were often used by patients within an hour of production.<ref name=\"Langmore\">{{cite book| editor-last=Langmore| editor-first=Diane| title=Australian Dictionary of Biography: Volume 17 1981-1990 A-K| publisher=[[Melbourne University Publishing]]| location=Carlton, Victoria| year=2009| page=129| isbn=978-0522853827}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Morris Iron Lung Thackray.jpg|thumb|right|Both-Nuffield iron lung display at the [[Thackray Medical Museum]], Leeds. Pictures show assembly at the Morris motor works]]\nVisiting London in 1938 during another polio epidemic, Both produced additional respirators there which attracted the attention of [[William Morris, 1st Viscount Nuffield|William Morris]] (Lord Nuffield), a British motor manufacturer and philanthropist. Nuffield, intrigued by the design, financed the production of approximately 1700 machines at his [[Morris Motors|car factory]] in [[Cowley, Oxfordshire|Cowley]], and donated them to hospitals throughout all parts of Britain and the British Empire.<ref name=\"Langmore\" /> Soon, the Both-Nuffield respirators were able to be produced by the thousand at about one-thirteenth the cost of the American design.<ref name=\"Healey\" /> By the early 1950s, there were over 700 Both-Nuffield iron lungs in the United Kingdom, but only 50 Drinker devices.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lawrence|first=Ghislaine|title=The Smith-Clarke Respirator|journal=[[The Lancet]]|date=2002-02-23|volume=359|pmid=11879908|issue=9307|page=716|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(02)07819-4}}</ref>\n\n==Modern usage==\n[[Image:Poumon artificiel.jpg|thumb|Staff in a [[Rhode Island]] hospital are examining a patient in an iron lung tank respirator during a polio epidemic in Rhode Island in 1960. The iron lung encased the [[thoracic cavity]] in an air-tight chamber used to create a negative pressure around the thoracic cavity, thereby causing air to enter the lungs to equalize [[Breathing#Mechanics|intrapulmonary pressure]] ]]\nRows of iron lungs filled hospital wards at the height of the polio outbreaks of the 1940s and 1950s, helping children, and some adults, with bulbar polio and bulbospinal polio. A polio patient with a paralyzed diaphragm would typically spend two weeks inside an iron lung while recovering.<ref name=\"NMAH\">{{Cite web| url=http://amhistory.si.edu/polio/howpolio/ironlung.htm| title=NMAH &#124; Polio: The Iron Lung and Other Equipment| website=[[National Museum of American History]]| publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]]| accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2012/01/what-america-looked-like-polio-children-paralyzed-in-iron-lungs/251098/|title=What America Looked Like: Polio Children Paralyzed in Iron Lungs|first=Brian|last=Resnick|date=January 10, 2012|website=The Atlantic}}</ref>\n\n[[Polio vaccine|Polio vaccination]] programs have virtually [[Poliomyelitis eradication|eradicated]] new cases of poliomyelitis in the developed world. Because of this, and the development of modern [[Medical ventilator|ventilators]], and widespread use of [[tracheal intubation]] and [[tracheotomy]], the iron lung has mostly disappeared from modern medicine. In 1959, there were 1,200 people using tank respirators in the United States, but by 2004 there were only 39.<ref name=\"NMAH\" /> By 2014, there were only 10 people left with an iron lung.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/aug/24/north-texan-one-of-10-still-living-in-iron-lung/| title=North Texan one of 10 still living in iron lung| first=Shelly| last=Conlon| date=24 August 2014| agency=Associated Press| publisher=The Washington Times| accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Positive pressure ventilation]] systems are now more common than negative pressure systems. Positive pressure ventilators work by blowing air into the patient's lungs via [[intubation]] through the airway; they were used for the first time in [[Blegdams Hospital]], [[Copenhagen]], Denmark, during a polio outbreak in 1952.<ref name=Reisner2009>{{cite web|author=Louise Reisner-S\u00e9n\u00e9lar|title=The Danish anaesthesiologist Bj\u00f6rn Ibsen a pioneer of long-term ventilation on the upper airways|year=2009|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B7CdB217pf6yN2QxOGI5NTUtZWIzYS00N2NhLWFhODQtOGZjMjdhZTlkZGE5&hl=de|accessdate=2011-07-01}}</ref><ref name=Wackers1994>{{cite book|last=Wackers|first=Ger|chapter=Chapter 4: |title=Theaters of truth and competence. Intermittent positive pressure respiration during the 1952 polio-epidemic in Copenhagen|year=1994|chapter-url=http://www.fdcw.unimaas.nl/personal/WebSitesMWT/Wackers/proefschrift.html#h4|accessdate=2011-07-01|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223223131/http://www.fdcw.unimaas.nl/personal/WebSitesMWT/Wackers/proefschrift.html#h4|archivedate=2007-12-23}}</ref> It proved a success and soon superseded the iron lung throughout Europe.\n\nThe iron lung now has a marginal place in modern [[respiratory therapy]]. Most patients with paralysis of the breathing muscles use modern [[mechanical ventilation|mechanical ventilators]] that push air into the airway with positive pressure. These are generally efficacious and have the advantage of not restricting patients' movements or caregivers' ability to examine the patients as significantly as an iron lung does. However, [[wikt:negative pressure|negative pressure]] ventilation is a truer approximation of normal physiological breathing and results in more normal distribution of air in the lungs. It may also be preferable in certain rare conditions, such as [[central hypoventilation syndrome]], in which failure of the medullary respiratory centers at the base of the brain results in patients having no [[Autonomic nervous system|autonomic control]] of breathing. At least one reported polio patient, [[Dianne Odell]], had a spinal deformity that caused the use of mechanical ventilators to be [[contraindicated]].<ref name=Sydney2008>{{cite news|author=|title=Power failure kills iron lung lady|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=2008-05-29|url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/world/power-failure-kills-iron-lung-lady/2008/05/29/1211654160059.html|accessdate=2011-07-01}}</ref> There are patients who today still use the older machines, often in their homes, despite the occasional difficulty of finding the various replacement parts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/60-years-iron-lung-us-polio-survivor-worries-about-new-2D11641456|title=60 years in an iron lung: US polio survivor worries about new global threat|publisher=}}</ref> Joan Headley of [[Post-Polio Health International]] said that as of May 28, 2008, there were about 30 patients in the U.S. still using an iron lung.<ref name=CNN2008>{{cite news|title=Woman dies after life spent in iron lung |date=May 28, 2008 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/05/28/iron.lung.death.ap/index.html |accessdate=2011-07-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022162511/http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/05/28/iron.lung.death.ap/index.html |archivedate=October 22, 2008 }}</ref> That figure may be inaccurately low; [[Houston, Texas|Houston]] alone had 19 iron lung patients living at home in 2008.<ref name=Neergaard2009>{{cite news|author=Lauran Neergaard|title=Emergency officials struggle to find those on life-support during power outages|date=2009-01-13|url=http://www.ems1.com/survivability/articles/447100-Emergency-officials-struggle-to-find-those-on-life-support-during-power-outages|accessdate=2014-01-01}}</ref> [[Martha Mason (writer)|Martha Mason]] of [[Lattimore, North Carolina]], died on May 4, 2009, after spending 60 of her 72 years in an iron lung.<ref name=Fox2009>{{cite news|last=Fox|first=Margalit|title=Martha Mason, Who Wrote Book About Her Decades in an Iron Lung, Dies at 71|work=The New York Times|date=2009-05-10|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/10/us/10mason.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=iron%20lung&st=cse|accessdate=2011-07-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October 2009, [[June Middleton]] of [[Melbourne, Australia]], who had been entered in the ''[[Guinness Book of Records]]'' as the person who spent the longest time in an iron lung, died aged 83, having spent more than 60 years in her iron lung.<ref name=Sydney2009>{{cite news|author=|title=Dead after 60 years in iron lung|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=2009-11-01|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/dead-after-60-years-in-iron-lung-20091101-hqyy.html?autostart=1|accessdate=2011-07-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the [[Post-Polio Health International]] (PHI) organizations estimated that there were only six to eight iron lung users in the United States; as of 2017 its executive director knew of none. Press reports then emerged, however, of at least three (perhaps the last three)<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=MAZZIOTTA |first1=JULIE |title=Polio Survivor, 82, Is One of the Last 3 People in the U.S. to Use an Iron Lung |url=https://people.com/health/polio-survivor-last-3-people-use-iron-lung/ |magazine=People Magazine |date=August 21, 2018}}</ref> users of such devices,<ref name=\"The Last of the Iron Lungs\">{{Cite web |url=https://gizmodo.com/the-last-of-the-iron-lungs-1819079169 |title=The Last of the Iron Lungs |last=Brown |first=Jennings |date=2017-11-20 |website=Gizmodo |accessdate=2017-11-25}}</ref> sparking interest amongst those in the [[makerspace]] community such as [[Naomi Wu]]<ref name=\"Parts for an Iron Lung\">{{Cite web |url=https://hackaday.com/2017/11/25/a-callout-parts-for-an-iron-lung/ |title=A Callout: Parts for an Iron Lung |last=Lewin |first=Day |date=2017-11-25 |website=Hackaday |accessdate=2017-11-25}}</ref> in the manufacture of the obsolete components, particularly the gaskets.<ref name=\"Running out of collars for her iron lung.\">{{Cite tweet |number=933619850806620167 |user=reaksexycyborg |title=Via @NireBryce- we've got a nice old lady running out of collars for her iron lung. Lot of \ud83d\udca9 going on in the world we can't do anything about- but this seems 100% doable. @hackaday, @make, textile tech folks- any ideas? From https://gizmodo.com/the-last-of-the-iron-lungs-1819079169 \u2026 |author=Naomi Wu |date=2017-11-23}}</ref> Another is retired lawyer Paul Alexander, 72, of Dallas.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/world/americas/104416976/living-inside-a-canister-this-polio-survivor-is-one-of-few-people-left-using-iron-lung |title=Living inside a canister: this polio survivor is one of few people left using iron lung |publisher=Stuff (Fairfax) |date= 1 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2020, reacting to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], to address the urgent global shortage of modern [[Medical ventilator|ventilators]] (needed for patients with advanced, severe [[COVID-19]] disease), some enterprises developed prototypes of new, readily-producible versions of the iron lung. These developments included:\n* a compact, torso-sized \"exovent\" developed by a team in the [[United Kingdom]], which included the [[University of Warwick]], the [[Royal National Throat Nose and Ear Hospital]], the [[Marshall Aerospace and Defence Group]], the [[Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust]], along with teams of medical clinicians, academics, manufacturers, engineers and citizen scientists;<ref name=\"modern_iron_lung_2020_04_06_newatlas\" /> \n* a full-size iron lung developed in the [[United States]] by a team led by Hays Services, Inc., of [[Hays, Kansas]].<ref name=\"one_kansas_company_2020_04_09_ksn_com\" /><ref name=\"hess_offers_2020_04_09_hdnews_net\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last1=Emerson|first1=JH|authorlink1=John Haven Emerson|last2=Loynes|first2=JA|title=The evolution of iron lungs: respirators of the body-encasing type|publisher=J.H. Emerson Company|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|year=1978}}\n* [[Martha Mason (writer)|Martha Mason]], a polio survivor, penned a best-selling memoir, ''Breath'', about her life inside an iron lung.\n* [[Margaret Atwood]] mentions an iron lung in her book ''Cat's Eye''\n* [[Peg Kehret]] mentions the use of an iron lung in her autobiographical book, ''[[Small Steps: The Year I Got Polio]]''\n* [[Elizabeth Berg (author)|Elizabeth Berg]] shares a fictionalization of the true story of Pat Raming, the first woman to give birth to baby while in an iron lung, in her book, We are all Welcome Here. 2006.\n* [http://ariwatch.com/VS/TheIronLung/RespirationWithoutBreathing.htm Respiration Without Breathing] - about the Thunberg \"barospirator\" built by John Emerson.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Iron lungs}}\n* [http://historical.hsl.virginia.edu/ironlung/ \"Iron Lung.\"] Claude Moore Health Sciences Library, [[University of Virginia]]\n* [http://www.powerhousemuseum.com/australia_innovates/?Section_id=1030&article_id=10022&behaviour=view_article Both respirator] at the [[Powerhouse Museum]]\n\n{{Respiratory system procedures}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|History}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iron Lung}}\n[[Category:Medical pumps]]\n[[Category:Polio]]\n[[Category:Respiratory therapy]]\n[[Category:1928 introductions]]\n[[Category:Mechanical ventilation]]\n", "name_user": "Penlite", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix wikilink, again", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron_lung"}
{"title_page": "Mass in B minor structure", "text_new": "{{short description|Structure of the movements in Bach's Mass in B minor}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Infobox Bach composition\n| name                = 'Mass in B minor'\n| image               = BWV 232 Titelblatt Missa.jpg\n| alt                 = front page of the autograph of the first book, listing the title, the scoring and the abbreviated name of the composer on pale paper\n| caption             = Autograph of the title page of the first book, Missa\n| bwv                 = 232\n| related             = [[Bach's Missa of 1733]]; several movements [[Parody music|parodies]] of [[List of Bach cantatas|cantata]] movements\n| form                = [[Missa solemnis]]\n| text                = Latin [[Mass (music)|Mass]]\n| composed            = {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1748}}?|end_date={{End date|1749}}|location=[[Leipzig]]}}\n| movements           = 27 in 4 parts (12 + 9 + 1 + 5)\n| vocal               = {{flatlist|\n* 2 choirs [[SATB|{{abbr|SATB|soprano, alto, tenor and bass}}]]\n* {{nowrap|solo: 2 [[soprano]]s, [[alto]], [[tenor]] and [[Bass (voice type)|bass]]}}\n}}\n| instrumental        = {{hlist | 3 trumpets | timpani | corno da caccia | 2 flauti traversi | 2 oboes | 2 oboes d'amore | 2 bassoons | 2 violins | viola | continuo }}\n| italic title        = no\n}}\nThe [[Mass in B minor]] is [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]'s only setting of the complete [[Latin]] text of the {{lang|la|[[Order of Mass|Ordinarium missae]]|italic=no}}.{{sfnp|Wolf|2011}} Towards the end of his life, mainly in 1748 and 1749, he finished composing new sections and compiling it into a complex, unified structure.\n\nBach structured the work in four parts:{{sfnp|J.S. Bach Mass in B Minor|1996}}\n\n#'''{{lang|la|Missa|italic=no}}'''\n#'''{{lang|la|Symbolum Nicenum|italic=no}}'''\n#'''{{lang|la|Sanctus|italic=no}}'''\n#{{lang|la|'''Osanna''', Benedictus, Agnus Dei et Dona nobis pacem|italic=no}}\n\nThe four sections of the manuscript are numbered, and Bach's usual closing formula (S.D.G = {{lang|la|[[Soli Deo Gloria]]|italic=no}}) is found at the end of the {{lang|la|Dona nobis pacem|italic=no}}.\n\nSome parts of the mass were used in Latin even in [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] Leipzig, and Bach had composed them: five settings of the [[Missa (Bach)|Missa]], containing the {{lang|grc|[[Kyrie]]|italic=no}} and the {{lang|la|[[Gloria in Excelsis Deo|Gloria]]|italic=no}}, and several additional individual settings of the {{lang|grc|Kyrie}} and the {{lang|la|[[Sanctus]]}}. To achieve the {{lang|la|[[Missa brevis|Missa tota]]|italic=no}}, a setting of the complete text of the mass, he combined his most elaborate Missa, the [[Bach's Missa of 1733|Missa in B minor, written in 1733]] for the court in [[Dresden]], and a {{lang|la|Sanctus|italic=no}} written for Christmas of 1724. He added a few new compositions, but mostly derived movements from [[List of Bach cantatas|cantata]] movements, in a technique known as [[Parody music|parody]].\n\nThe Mass is a [[compendium]] of many different styles in vocal composition, in both the \"[[Prima pratica|stile antico]]\" reminiscent of [[Renaissance music]] (even containing [[Gregorian chant]]) and the [[Baroque music|Baroque]] concertante style of his own time: [[fugal]] writing and dances, [[aria]]s and a movement for two four-part choirs. Similar to [[Baroque architecture|architecture of the period]], Bach achieved a symmetry of parts, with the profession of faith ({{lang|la|Credo|italic=no}}) in the center and the {{lang|la|Crucifixus|italic=no}} in its center. Bach scored the work for five vocal parts (two [[soprano]]s, [[alto]], [[tenor]] and [[Bass (voice type)|bass]], [[SATB|SSATB]]). While some choral movements are for only four parts, the {{lang|la|Sanctus|italic=no}} is scored for six voices (SSAATB), and the {{lang|la|Osanna|italic=no}} even for two four-part choirs. Bach called for a rich [[Baroque instruments|instrumentation]] of brass, woodwinds and strings, assigning varied [[obbligato]] parts to different instruments.\n\n== History and parody ==\n\nThe Mass was Bach's last major artistic undertaking. The reason for the composition is unknown.{{sfnp|Wolf|2011}} Scholars have found no plausible occasion for which the work may have been intended. Joshua Rifkin notes:\n<blockquote>... likely, Bach sought to create a paradigmatic example of vocal composition while at the same time contributing to the venerable musical genre of the Mass, still the most demanding and prestigious apart from opera.{{sfnp|Rifkin|2006}}</blockquote>\n\n[[File:Missa in B Minor (\"Kyrie\" and \"Gloria\" of the B Minor Mass) WDL11619.pdf|thumb|upright|Title page for the Missa for Dresden from 1733]]\nBach first composed [[Bach's Missa of 1733|a setting of the Kyrie and Gloria in 1733]] for the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] royal court in Dresden. He presented that composition to [[Frederick Augustus II, Elector of Saxony]] (later, as Augustus III, also king of Poland),{{sfnp|Wolf|2011}} accompanied by a letter:<blockquote>In deepest Devotion I present to your Royal Highness this small product of that science which I have attained in Musique, with the most humble request that you will deign to regard it not according to the imperfection of its Composition, but with a most gracious eye&nbsp;... and thus take me into your most mighty Protection.{{sfnp|Talbeck|2002}}</blockquote> He arranged the text in diverse movements for a five-part choir and solo voices, according to the taste in Dresden where sacred music \"borrowed\" from Italian opera with a focus on choral movements, as [[Musicology|musicologist]] Arthur Wenk notes.{{sfnp|Wenk|2011|p=4}}\n\n[[File:Johann Sebastian Bach 1746.jpg|thumb|upright| left|Johann Sebastian Bach towards the end of his life, by  [[Elias Gottlob Haussmann]], 1746|alt=portrait of Bach towards the end of his life, posing in a dark outfit with a wig, holding a single sheet of music in his right hand, facing the viewer with a serious expression]]\nBach expanded the Missa of 1733 to a {{lang|la|Missa tota|italic=no}} from 1748 to 1749, near the end of his life.{{sfnp|Rifkin|2006}}{{sfnp|Sherman|2004}}{{sfnp|Libbey|2009}} In these last years, he added three choral movements for the {{lang|de|Credo|italic=no}}: its opening {{lang|de|Credo in unum Deum|italic=no}}, {{lang|de|Confiteor|italic=no}} and Et incarnatus est. The Sanctus was originally an individual movement composed for Christmas 1724 in [[Leipzig]].{{sfnp|Wolf|2011}}\n\nMost other movements of the mass are [[Parody music|parodies]] of music from earlier [[Bach cantata|cantata]]s,{{sfnp|Libbey|2009}} dating back as far as 1714. Wenk points out that Bach often used parody to \"bring a composition to a higher level of perfection\".{{sfnp|Wenk|2011|p=6}} The original musical sources of several movements are known, for others they are lost but the score shows that they are copied and reworked. Bach selected movements that carried a similar expression and ''[[affekt]]''. For example, {{lang|la|Gratias agimus tibi|italic=no}} (We give you thanks) is based on {{lang|de|[[Wir danken dir, Gott, wir danken dir, BWV 29|Wir danken dir, Gott, wir danken dir]]}}{{sfnp|P\u00e9rez Torres|2005|p=5}} (We thank you, God, we thank you) and the {{lang|la|Crucifixus|italic=no}} (Crucified) is based on the general lamenting about the situation of the faithful Christian, {{lang|de|[[Weinen, Klagen, Sorgen, Zagen, BWV 12|Weinen, Klagen, Sorgen, Zagen]]}}{{sfnp|P\u00e9rez Torres|2005|p=5}} (Weeping, lamenting, worrying, fearing) which Bach had composed already in 1714 as one of his first cantatas for the court of [[Weimar]].\n\nBach quoted Gregorian chant twice, in the {{lang|de|Credo in unum Deum|italic=no}} as a [[Theme (music)|theme]] and in the {{lang|de|Confiteor|italic=no}} as a [[cantus firmus]] embedded in complex [[polyphony]].\n\n[[File:Friedrichsthalgotha.jpg|thumb|Schloss Friedrichsthal|alt=The symmetrical structure of Schloss Friedrichsthal, seen through the front gate to the property]]\nBach achieved a symmetry of the parts, with the profession of faith ({{lang|la|Credo|italic=no}}) in the center and the movement {{lang|la|Crucifixus|italic=no}} in its center. Markus Rathey, Associate Professor of Music History at the Institute of Sacred Music at the [[Yale School of Music]], sees a similarity to architecture of the period, such as the [[Palace of Versailles]]. Bach knew buildings in that style, for example {{ill|Schloss Friedrichsthal|de}} in Gotha, built in 1710.{{sfnp|Rathey|2003|pp=2\u20134}} Rathey continues:\n<blockquote>The symmetry on earth mirrors the symmetric perfection of heaven. The purpose of art at this time\u2014in architecture, the visual arts, and music\u2014was not to create something entirely new, but to reflect this divine perfection, and in this way to praise God. We find such a symmetric outline in many pieces by Johann Sebastian Bach,19 but only in a few cases is this outline as consequent as in the B Minor Mass.{{sfnp|Rathey|2003|p=4}}</blockquote> The parts Kyrie, Gloria and Credo are all designed with choral sections as the outer movements, framing an intimate center of theological significance.\n\nAccording to [[Christoph Wolff]], the Mass can be seen as a \"kind of specimen book of his finest compositions in every kind of style, from the stile antico of Palestrina in the 'Credo' and 'Confiteor' and the expressively free writing of the 'Crucifixus' and 'Agnus Dei', to the supreme counterpoint of the opening Kyrie as well as so many other choruses, right up to the most modern style in galant solos like 'Christe eleison' and 'Domine Deus'\".{{sfnp|Jenkins|2001|p=2}} Bach made \"a conscious effort to incorporate all styles that were available to him, to encompass all music history as far as it was accessible\".{{sfnp|Butt|1991|p=78}} The Mass is a [[compendium]] of vocal sacred music, similar to other collections that Bach compiled during the last decade of his life, such as the [[Clavier-\u00dcbung III]], ''[[The Art of Fugue]]'', the ''[[Goldberg Variations]]'', the [[Great Eighteen Chorale Preludes]] and ''[[The Musical Offering]]''.{{sfnp|Wenk|2011|p=7}}\n\n== Overview ==\n\nGiven Bach's Lutheran background and the history of the composition, developed over several decades, he deviated from the typical structure of the mass in five parts, {{lang|grc|Kyrie|italic=no}}, {{lang|la|Gloria|italic=no}}, {{lang|la|Credo|italic=no}}, {{lang|la|Sanctus|italic=no}} and {{lang|la|Agnus Dei|italic=no}}. He had composed the {{lang|la|Sanctus|italic=no}} in 1724, and the {{lang|la|Missa|italic=no}} (consisting of the {{lang|grc|Kyrie|italic=no}} and the {{lang|la|Gloria|italic=no}}) in 1733. When he compiled the mass, he used these parts, added the {{lang|la|Credo|italic=no}}, including new compositions, and concluded with {{lang|la|[[Osanna]]|italic=no}}, which is normally part of the {{lang|la|Sanctus|italic=no}}.\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n|+ Comparison of Bach's titles to the parts of the mass\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Five usual sections of the<br />[[Mass (music)#Ordinarium|Mass&nbsp;ordinary]]\n! scope=\"col\" | Mass in B&nbsp;minor sections\n! scope=\"col\" | Number of movements\n! scope=\"col\" | Year from\n! scope=\"col\" | Year to\n! scope=\"col\" | Notes\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | I.&nbsp;{{lang|la|[[Kyrie]]|italic=no}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" | {{nowrap|I. {{lang|la|[[#No. 1 Missa|Missa]]|italic=no}} (consisting of {{lang|la|[[#Kyrie I|Kyrie]]|italic=no}}}}<br />and {{lang|la|[[#Gloria|Gloria]]|italic=no}})\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 3 || 1733 || 1733 || symmetry, {{nowrap|central duet}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | II.&nbsp;{{lang|la|[[Gloria in excelsis Deo|Gloria]]|italic=no}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 9 || ? || 1733 || symmetry, {{nowrap|central duet}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | III.&nbsp;{{lang|la|[[Credo]]|italic=no}}\n! II.&nbsp;{{lang|la|[[#No. 2 Symbolum Nicenum|Symbolum Nicenum]]|italic=no}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 9 || 1714 || 1749 || symmetry, {{nowrap|central Crucifixus}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | IV.&nbsp;{{lang|la|[[Sanctus]]|italic=no}}<br />{{nowrap|including {{lang|la|[[Hosanna]]|italic=no}} and {{lang|la|[[Benedictus]]|italic=no}}}}\n! III.&nbsp;{{lang|la|[[#No. 3 Sanctus|Sanctus]]|italic=no}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2 || 1724 || 1724 || \n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | IV.&nbsp;{{lang|la|[[#No. 4 Osanna, Benedictus, Agnus Dei et Dona nobis pacem|Osanna, Benedictus,<br />Agnus Dei et<br />Dona nobis pacem]]|italic=no}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 3 || 1732 || 1749 || \n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | V.&nbsp;{{lang|la|[[Agnus Dei (music)|Agnus Dei]]|italic=no}}<br />ending on \"{{lang|la|dona nobis pacem|italic=no}}\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2 || 1725 || 1749 ||\n|-\n|}\n\n== Scoring ==\n\n[[File:Baroque orchestra L'arpa festante.JPG|thumb|300px|Players of the Baroque orchestra [[L'arpa festante]] rehearsing the Gloria in [[St. Martin, Idstein]], natural trumpets and timpani on the right, flauti traversi in the background|alt=players of the Baroque orchestra [[L'arpa festante]] rehearsing with a choir, with part of the continuo organ's keyboard in the foreground, three players of natural trumpets standing on the right, the timpani player sitting between them and the organ, flauti traversi in the background]]\nThe work is scored for five vocal soloists, chorus and orchestra. Its movements are listed in a table with the scoring of [[Voice type|voice]]s and instruments, [[Key (music)|key]], [[Tempo|tempo marking]], [[time signature]] and source. The movement numbering follows the [[B\u00e4renreiter]] edition of the [[Neue Bach-Ausgabe]], first in a consecutive numbering ([[NBA (Bach)|NBA]] II), then in a numbering for the four individual parts (NBA I).\n\nThe voices are abbreviated S for [[soprano]], A for [[alto]], T for [[tenor]], B for [[Bass (voice type)|bass]]. Bach asked for two sopranos. Practical performances often have only one soprano soloist, sharing the parts for the second soprano (SII) between soprano and alto. A four-part choir is indicated by [[SATB]], a five-part choir by SSATB. The {{lang|la|Sanctus|italic=no}} requires six vocal parts, SSAATB, which are often divided in the three upper voices versus the lower voices. The {{lang|la|Osanna|italic=no}} requires two choirs SATB.\n\n[[Baroque instruments|Instruments in the orchestra]] are three [[trumpet]]s (Tr), [[timpani]] (Ti), [[Natural horn|corno da caccia]] (Co), two [[Flauto traverso|flauti traversi]] (Ft), two [[oboe]]s (Ob), two [[Oboe d'amore|oboes d'amore]] (Oa), two [[bassoon]]s (Fg), two [[violin]]s (Vl), [[viola]] (Va), and [[Figured bass#Basso continuo|basso continuo]]. The continuo is not mentioned in the table as it is present all the time. The other instruments are grouped by brass, woodwinds and strings. \n\nBach based movements of the Mass in B minor on earlier compositions. What is known about reworked earlier material is indicated in the last two columns of the table (earlier composition; year of composition), including some educated guesswork, as found in the indicated scholarly literature. This does not include the 1733 version of Part I (the movements that constitute the {{lang|la|Kyrie}} and {{lang|la|Gloria}}), but earlier compositions which Bach used as basis for that version.\n\n== Structure ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+ Structure of ''Mass in B Minor'' by J. S. Bach\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" | Section\n! colspan=\"5\" | Instruments\n! colspan=\"3\" | Music\n! colspan=\"2\" | Origination\n|-style=\"height: 4em;\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | <small>{{nowrap|[[Neue Bach-Ausgabe|NBA]] II}}</small>\n! scope=\"col\" | <small>{{nowrap|[[Neue Bach-Ausgabe|NBA]] I}}</small>\n! scope=\"col\" | Incipit \n! scope=\"col\" | Solo\n! scope=\"col\" | Choir\n! scope=\"col\" | Brass\n! scope=\"col\" | Wood\n! scope=\"col\"