vh.home.xs4all.nl/HM/incarnatus.pdf \"Et incarnatus\": An Afterthought? / Against the \"Revisionist\" View of Bach's B-Minor Mass]. ''Journal of Musicological Research'', 2004\n* [http://www.worshipanew.net/music/choral/MassInBMinor.htm B Minor Mass Explorer] worshipanew.net\n\n{{Masses and Magnificats by Johann Sebastian Bach}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Mass in B minor structure}}\n\n[[Category:Masses by Johann Sebastian Bach]]\n[[Category:1749 compositions]]\n[[Category:Compositions in B minor]]\n", "name_user": "Francis Schonken", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOverview:tweaks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_in_B_minor_structure"}
{"title_page": "1888 Princeton Tigers football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1888\n| team = Princeton Tigers\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| conference = Independent\n| record = 11\u20131\n| head_coach = None\n| off_scheme = \n| def_scheme = \n| captain = [[Hector Cowan]]\n| stadium = \n}}\n{{1888 Eastern college football independents records}}\nThe '''1888 Princeton Tigers football team''' represented [[Princeton University]] in the [[1888 college football season]]. The team compiled an 11\u20131 record.  The team held its first ten opponents scoreless, winning those games by a combined 589 to 0 score. The team's sole loss was by a 10-0 score in the final game of the season against an undefeated [[1888 Yale Bulldogs football team|Yale team]] that has been recognized as the 1888 [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|national champion]].<ref name=SR>{{cite web|title=1888 Princeton Tigers Schedule and Results|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=SR/College Football|accessdate=February 27, 2017|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/princeton/1888-schedule.html}}</ref>\n\nThe practice of selecting All-American football teams began the following year with the [[1890 College Football All-America Team]]. However, Princeton's roster in 1888 included a number of star players, including fullback [[Knowlton Ames|Knowlton \"Snake\" Ames]], end [[Jesse Riggs]], right tackle [[Hector Cowan]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Football, The American Intercollegiate Game|author=[[Parke H. Davis]]|publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons|year=1917|pages=238, 385|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DbgHAQAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n|attend=yes\n|source=yes\n\n|September 29||{{cfb link|year=1888|team=Lehigh Engineers|title=Lehigh}}|[[University Field (Princeton)|University Field]]|[[Princeton, Ne